1
00:00:14,247 --> 00:00:15,515
ON THIS EPISODE

2
00:00:15,582 --> 00:00:17,884
I'm not too nervous today.

3
00:00:17,951 --> 00:00:20,987
It's been a year
since he stood before the counter here.

4
00:00:21,054 --> 00:00:22,655
First, mash the salmon roe.

5
00:00:22,956 --> 00:00:24,024
HE EVEN ADDS COMMENTS?

6
00:00:24,090 --> 00:00:26,493
I prepared something to eat on the side.

7
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:28,161
KANG-ROK HAS DONE A 180

8
00:00:29,362 --> 00:00:32,832
The best couple now faces each other.

9
00:00:32,899 --> 00:00:34,401
He probably has a secret weapon.

10
00:00:34,467 --> 00:00:35,935
I'll share the recipe if you pick me.

11
00:00:36,002 --> 00:00:37,470
I've never seen him tout.

12
00:00:37,537 --> 00:00:39,773
UP AGAINST HIM IS
THE DIABOLICAL WRECKAGE DINING

13
00:00:39,839 --> 00:00:40,840
-What?
-What's that?

14
00:00:40,907 --> 00:00:42,142
-What is that?
-It smells like <i>jwibullori</i>.

15
00:00:42,208 --> 00:00:43,243
HOW DID THE SON-POONG ROUND GO?

16
00:00:44,778 --> 00:00:47,447
He's looking at him. "Who is that guy?"

17
00:00:47,514 --> 00:00:48,748
A FEAST OF THE BEST DISHES YET

18
00:00:48,815 --> 00:00:51,651
The sauce is so good.
I want to have him as my master.

19
00:00:52,952 --> 00:00:55,155
WHICH CHEF RECEIVED HIS PRAISE?

20
00:00:55,221 --> 00:00:56,923
Welcome to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

21
00:00:56,990 --> 00:00:59,592
We're here today with Nana and Kyuhyun.

22
00:00:59,659 --> 00:01:02,862
-It's been 20 years since your debut?
-Yes.

23
00:01:02,929 --> 00:01:04,597
This is the 20th year.

24
00:01:04,664 --> 00:01:06,366
-That's amazing.
-It's been that long.

25
00:01:06,433 --> 00:01:08,168
Did you debut
when you were still a student?

26
00:01:09,202 --> 00:01:11,171
I debuted when I turned 20,

27
00:01:11,237 --> 00:01:13,773
back in 2006.

28
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:15,175
You're 40 now?

29
00:01:15,241 --> 00:01:16,276
-That happened.
-My gosh.

30
00:01:16,342 --> 00:01:17,710
HITTING MIDDLE AGE

31
00:01:17,777 --> 00:01:19,846
So instead of going, "We're SUPER JUNIOR,"

32
00:01:19,913 --> 00:01:21,881
we've been doing it like this.

33
00:01:21,948 --> 00:01:23,683
<i>Everyone is now in their forties.</i>

34
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:25,051
-<i>Everyone?</i>
-<i>Everyone is in their forties?</i>

35
00:01:25,618 --> 00:01:28,688
His group is nicknamed
Gwanggaeto the Great of the Korean Wave.

36
00:01:29,722 --> 00:01:31,591
-Gwanggaeto the Great?
-Exactly.

37
00:01:31,658 --> 00:01:32,759
They've conquered them all.

38
00:01:32,826 --> 00:01:35,028
<i>The first Korean boy group</i>
<i>to tour in South America</i>

39
00:01:35,095 --> 00:01:37,130
<i>and hold a concert in Saudi Arabia.</i>

40
00:01:37,197 --> 00:01:40,767
SUPER JUNIOR has recorded
many firsts in their career.

41
00:01:40,834 --> 00:01:44,137
We have also topped the chart in Taiwan
for over 150 weeks.

42
00:01:44,204 --> 00:01:46,673
-Topped the chart in Taiwan for 150 weeks.
-For 150 weeks?

43
00:01:46,739 --> 00:01:48,374
-That's about four years.
-Almost four years.

44
00:01:48,441 --> 00:01:49,442
That's insane.

45
00:01:49,509 --> 00:01:50,944
TEAM GWANGGAETO THE GREAT

46
00:01:51,010 --> 00:01:55,415
One of our chefs can testify
to SUPER JUNIOR's global popularity.

47
00:01:55,482 --> 00:01:56,483
Amy Park?

48
00:01:56,549 --> 00:01:57,851
-Yes?
-Yes.

49
00:01:57,917 --> 00:01:59,686
-"Amy Park."
-Yes, Amy.

50
00:01:59,752 --> 00:02:02,255
When I, Amy, worked in Hong Kong…

51
00:02:02,589 --> 00:02:04,057
WHAT'S WITH THAT TONE?

52
00:02:04,124 --> 00:02:07,961
…he asked if he could make a reservation
at the restaurant, so I helped him.

53
00:02:08,027 --> 00:02:10,096
At the restaurant I worked,
I had colleagues

54
00:02:10,163 --> 00:02:13,366
who were from South America
and Southeast Asia.

55
00:02:13,433 --> 00:02:16,035
I didn't think
they would be familiar with SUPER JUNIOR,

56
00:02:16,102 --> 00:02:19,005
so I wrote the reservation down
for "Amy's friend."

57
00:02:19,072 --> 00:02:21,875
But when he came,
the whole restaurant went crazy.

58
00:02:21,941 --> 00:02:25,178
-"You didn't say SUPER JUNIOR was coming!"
-"Why didn't you say so?"

59
00:02:25,245 --> 00:02:27,180
I was there to do a solo concert.

60
00:02:27,247 --> 00:02:30,383
I remember visiting the restaurant,
taking pictures, and having fun.

61
00:02:30,450 --> 00:02:32,185
So I was quite proud that day.

62
00:02:32,252 --> 00:02:35,655
-"I'm friends with SUPER JUNIOR."
-"Oh, she was friends with them?"

63
00:02:35,722 --> 00:02:37,023
KYUHYUN MADE AMY'S DAY

64
00:02:37,090 --> 00:02:38,324
It felt nice.

65
00:02:38,391 --> 00:02:40,760
Not only is he an excellent singer,

66
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:43,596
-but he's also an excellent cook.
-He's a good cook.

67
00:02:43,663 --> 00:02:47,100
We need to verify this claim.

68
00:02:47,167 --> 00:02:50,203
He was offered a spot
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>!

69
00:02:50,270 --> 00:02:52,305
-Are you serious?
-This rumor went around.

70
00:02:52,572 --> 00:02:53,673
HE'S THAT GOOD?

71
00:02:53,740 --> 00:02:55,341
We must do a fact check.

72
00:02:55,408 --> 00:02:58,545
Please don't take this the wrong way
and hear me out.

73
00:02:58,611 --> 00:03:00,914
The production crew
who produced <i>Culinary Class Wars</i> said,

74
00:03:00,980 --> 00:03:03,750
"We're doing a program
called <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>."

75
00:03:03,816 --> 00:03:05,818
"Since you like to cook,
would you like to join?"

76
00:03:05,885 --> 00:03:08,721
That was all they said to me.

77
00:03:08,788 --> 00:03:12,258
Word got around
and turned into a rumor about an offer.

78
00:03:12,325 --> 00:03:15,195
-Asking you to join is an offer.
-That's an offer.

79
00:03:15,261 --> 00:03:17,130
-Is that so?
-Of course.

80
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:19,766
-And they don't bring it up to anyone.
-That's true.

81
00:03:19,832 --> 00:03:22,602
-Would they ask Sung-ju?
-I never got an offer.

82
00:03:22,669 --> 00:03:24,971
-I'll count that as an offer then.
-It was.

83
00:03:25,305 --> 00:03:27,140
CONFIDENCE UP

84
00:03:27,207 --> 00:03:28,508
If you had competed,

85
00:03:28,575 --> 00:03:31,978
-among the chefs in the studio…
-Everyone here has been on that show.

86
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:34,147
…which one could you have had
a chance against?

87
00:03:34,214 --> 00:03:35,248
BROWSING

88
00:03:35,315 --> 00:03:37,283
There are Nam-no, Eun-yeong, and Sung-jun.

89
00:03:37,350 --> 00:03:40,086
-This is an if question, right?
-Yes.

90
00:03:40,153 --> 00:03:41,287
I'd like to fight Poong.

91
00:03:41,588 --> 00:03:43,089
CHOSEN

92
00:03:43,156 --> 00:03:44,290
But I wasn't on the show.

93
00:03:44,857 --> 00:03:47,660
If he had, we would've been
the biggest rivals.

94
00:03:48,228 --> 00:03:50,063
Why don't we have him here, then?

95
00:03:50,129 --> 00:03:51,431
Should we?

96
00:03:51,497 --> 00:03:53,032
I don't think I'm that good.

97
00:03:53,099 --> 00:03:55,168
We can make room for him.

98
00:03:55,235 --> 00:03:57,136
-Let's get rid of this one.
-Should we?

99
00:03:57,470 --> 00:03:59,239
A DECISION MADE FOR KYUHYUN

100
00:03:59,305 --> 00:04:01,307
I can always sit here.

101
00:04:01,874 --> 00:04:03,643
WHAT A RELIEF

102
00:04:03,710 --> 00:04:06,346
I hear Kyuhyun has
even made Beef Wellington.

103
00:04:06,412 --> 00:04:07,647
-Wellington?
-Beef Wellington?

104
00:04:07,714 --> 00:04:09,415
It's not easy to make,
and it takes a while.

105
00:04:09,482 --> 00:04:13,286
-On a show called <i>Cookking</i>.
-Yes, there was that show.

106
00:04:13,353 --> 00:04:16,022
I had to make something in 30 minutes.

107
00:04:16,089 --> 00:04:19,993
<i>That dish takes a while to make</i>
<i>and the process is rather complicated,</i>

108
00:04:20,059 --> 00:04:22,495
<i>but it came out looking perfect.</i>

109
00:04:22,562 --> 00:04:24,597
He recreated it perfectly.

110
00:04:24,664 --> 00:04:25,798
It was delicious.

111
00:04:25,865 --> 00:04:28,568
It's not an easy dish
even for proficient chefs,

112
00:04:28,635 --> 00:04:31,204
but I was surprised to see
how delicious it turned out.

113
00:04:31,271 --> 00:04:32,438
It was cooked perfectly too.

114
00:04:32,505 --> 00:04:34,607
-He's a genius.
-The chefs who tried it back then

115
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:35,708
all praised him for it.

116
00:04:35,775 --> 00:04:39,612
I often watch and study
the recipes these chefs cook with,

117
00:04:39,679 --> 00:04:41,180
so I consider them my teachers.

118
00:04:41,247 --> 00:04:42,715
What have you tried making?

119
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:45,184
I recently enjoyed watching
<i>Culinary Class Wars 2</i> very much.

120
00:04:45,251 --> 00:04:46,786
-And I tried Chef Kang-rok's dish…
-Mr. Braise.

121
00:04:46,853 --> 00:04:49,522
-…the one he made in the final round.
-That?

122
00:04:49,589 --> 00:04:52,292
I took notice of the ingredients
he used in the show

123
00:04:52,358 --> 00:04:54,427
and tried making it the same way.

124
00:04:54,494 --> 00:04:56,095
And was it good?

125
00:04:56,162 --> 00:04:57,230
It was so good.

126
00:04:57,297 --> 00:04:59,766
The soup was on a whole another dimension.

127
00:04:59,832 --> 00:05:03,636
Kyuhyun said he tried copying it
however he could, but it was still good.

128
00:05:03,703 --> 00:05:06,572
It must be because he's a good cook.

129
00:05:06,839 --> 00:05:08,274
THE WINNER APPROVES

130
00:05:08,341 --> 00:05:09,642
Can anybody make it good?

131
00:05:10,209 --> 00:05:11,911
-That's not the case.
-No, right?

132
00:05:11,978 --> 00:05:12,979
So not just anyone.

133
00:05:13,046 --> 00:05:15,682
-It was because Kang-rok made it.
-You're right.

134
00:05:15,748 --> 00:05:18,251
You even launched your own product?

135
00:05:18,318 --> 00:05:19,819
-Really?
-Really?

136
00:05:19,886 --> 00:05:21,621
-We have all the info.
-<i>Tteokbokki</i>.

137
00:05:21,688 --> 00:05:24,691
I really love <i>tteokbokki</i>,

138
00:05:24,757 --> 00:05:25,825
so I made Chotteok Kyutteok.

139
00:05:25,892 --> 00:05:27,560
-<i>Chotteok Kyutteok?</i>
-<i>From my name, Cho Kyu-hyun.</i>

140
00:05:27,627 --> 00:05:29,195
<i>It was for</i>
<i>a convenience store collaboration,</i>

141
00:05:29,262 --> 00:05:30,963
like a short event.

142
00:05:31,030 --> 00:05:33,700
How much do you have to like <i>tteokbokki</i>
to launch a product like that?

143
00:05:33,766 --> 00:05:35,535
I eat it really often,

144
00:05:35,601 --> 00:05:37,370
-up to three times a week.
-Three times?

145
00:05:37,437 --> 00:05:39,539
-That's a lot.
-I have a routine.

146
00:05:39,605 --> 00:05:41,441
When I drink the night before,

147
00:05:41,507 --> 00:05:44,577
I always eat <i>tteokbokki</i>
for dinner the next day.

148
00:05:44,644 --> 00:05:50,049
I've loved it since elementary school
until now, so almost 30 years now.

149
00:05:50,116 --> 00:05:53,319
Can you share your best <i>tteokbokki</i> joints?

150
00:05:53,386 --> 00:05:54,887
-I want to know.
-The good places.

151
00:05:54,954 --> 00:05:57,256
You would know
if you're a <i>tteokbokki</i> lover.

152
00:05:57,323 --> 00:05:59,826
You must know Sintoburi in Achasan.

153
00:05:59,892 --> 00:06:02,261
-Yes, that's my neighborhood.
-Sintoburi in Achasan.

154
00:06:02,328 --> 00:06:03,563
-It's so good.
-Really?

155
00:06:03,629 --> 00:06:04,864
I go and eat some there,

156
00:06:04,931 --> 00:06:06,899
get some to-go,
and keep it in the freezer.

157
00:06:06,966 --> 00:06:09,302
It's that good?
Is it near Achasan Station?

158
00:06:09,369 --> 00:06:12,004
Next, there's Jopok Topokki in Hongdae.

159
00:06:12,071 --> 00:06:13,740
-Jopok Topokki.
-They're open late.

160
00:06:13,806 --> 00:06:14,907
It's always been famous.

161
00:06:14,974 --> 00:06:17,377
Next, Golmok Tteokbokki
in Munjeong-dong is delicious too.

162
00:06:17,443 --> 00:06:18,945
Anything in Nowon-gu?

163
00:06:19,011 --> 00:06:20,380
In Seokgye Station in Nowon-gu,

164
00:06:20,446 --> 00:06:22,582
-there's a place called Oppa Saenggak.
-Oppa Saenggak.

165
00:06:22,648 --> 00:06:25,251
-I know.
-I've been a regular there

166
00:06:25,318 --> 00:06:27,019
-since middle school.
-Oppa Saenggak.

167
00:06:27,086 --> 00:06:29,555
Is there a chef here
who also loves <i>tteokbokki</i>?

168
00:06:29,622 --> 00:06:31,124
-I like <i>tteokbokki</i>.
-Nam-no.

169
00:06:31,190 --> 00:06:32,458
Any recommendations?

170
00:06:32,525 --> 00:06:34,394
There's Byeon Gangsoe
in Apgujeong Rodeo Street.

171
00:06:34,460 --> 00:06:36,829
-Byeon Gangsoe.
-That place is really good.

172
00:06:36,896 --> 00:06:38,831
-What was that?
-Byeon Gangsoe.

173
00:06:38,898 --> 00:06:40,299
Near Seoul Children's Grand Park,

174
00:06:40,366 --> 00:06:42,702
-there's Eunhye Tteokbokki. <i>Jjajang</i>.
-<i>Jjajang tteokbokki</i>.

175
00:06:42,769 --> 00:06:44,804
-I like Ruby Tteokbokki.
-Where's that?

176
00:06:44,871 --> 00:06:46,672
-Apgujeong.
-Apgujeong Rodeo Street.

177
00:06:46,739 --> 00:06:47,840
He knows all of them.

178
00:06:47,907 --> 00:06:49,776
-That's crazy.
-He knows every place.

179
00:06:50,109 --> 00:06:52,345
THE TTEOKBOKKI GPT
KNOWS EVERY TTEOKBOKKI JOINT

180
00:06:52,412 --> 00:06:54,080
There's the actual
authentic <i>tteokbokki</i> place.

181
00:06:54,147 --> 00:06:56,416
It actually started in Sindang-dong,

182
00:06:56,482 --> 00:06:57,984
-and there's an originator.
-Where?

183
00:06:58,551 --> 00:07:00,153
Jinmi Tteokbokki.

184
00:07:00,219 --> 00:07:02,221
I first went there 48 years ago.

185
00:07:02,288 --> 00:07:03,456
YOUNG HYUN-SUK'S TTEOKBOKKI JOINT

186
00:07:03,523 --> 00:07:05,425
-Forty-eight?
-Forty-eight years ago?

187
00:07:05,491 --> 00:07:07,093
It opened during the war.

188
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:08,828
Anything's good when you're a refugee.

189
00:07:08,895 --> 00:07:10,463
-Yes.
-Before I started school…

190
00:07:10,530 --> 00:07:12,231
Were you born in the 1940s?

191
00:07:12,298 --> 00:07:13,866
-I was born in 1972.
-The 1940s?

192
00:07:14,333 --> 00:07:16,302
QUITE IMPOLITE

193
00:07:16,369 --> 00:07:19,806
Back in my grade school days, everyone
from Heungin Elementary went there.

194
00:07:19,872 --> 00:07:21,674
That place is still in business,

195
00:07:21,741 --> 00:07:23,876
and it still tastes the same.

196
00:07:23,943 --> 00:07:25,578
The joint from 48 years ago still stands?

197
00:07:25,645 --> 00:07:27,480
-Right? It still stands.
-I'll try it.

198
00:07:27,547 --> 00:07:30,783
So you're saying each <i>tteokbokki</i> place
has its own taste, right?

199
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:32,018
-Of course.
-Right?

200
00:07:32,084 --> 00:07:34,187
-Completely.
-That's why we prepared this.

201
00:07:34,253 --> 00:07:37,757
Is he a true <i>tteokbokki</i> enthusiast?

202
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:40,359
-Or is he just pretending?
-No way.

203
00:07:40,426 --> 00:07:41,727
-A blind test?
-So we prepared

204
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:44,397
-a blind test.
-No, don't do this.

205
00:07:44,464 --> 00:07:48,167
We got some <i>tteokbokki</i>
from the famous joints he mentioned

206
00:07:48,234 --> 00:07:50,069
<i>and brought them here.</i>

207
00:07:50,136 --> 00:07:52,939
So just like <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

208
00:07:53,005 --> 00:07:55,408
-please cover your eyes first.
-We have to feed him.

209
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:57,543
-Yes, he needs someone to feed him.
-Where is it?

210
00:07:57,610 --> 00:07:59,111
Is the name written somewhere?

211
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:00,646
WHY, IT IS

212
00:08:00,713 --> 00:08:01,714
-He'll know.
-Can you see?

213
00:08:01,781 --> 00:08:04,150
Tell us which joint the <i>tteokbokki</i> is from

214
00:08:04,217 --> 00:08:08,387
-one after the other.
-It'll be insane if he gets this.

215
00:08:08,454 --> 00:08:09,856
-Can he do it?
-If he does, it'll be crazy.

216
00:08:09,922 --> 00:08:12,158
-Yes, it'll be insane.
-Should we start with that one?

217
00:08:12,225 --> 00:08:13,960
-All right.
-Let's go.

218
00:08:14,026 --> 00:08:17,363
Chef Sung-jun is about to feed
the first <i>tteokbokki</i> to Kyuhyun.

219
00:08:17,430 --> 00:08:18,931
Why can't we share?

220
00:08:18,998 --> 00:08:19,999
CHUCKLE

221
00:08:20,066 --> 00:08:21,767
-It tastes better when shared.
-Yes.

222
00:08:21,834 --> 00:08:23,870
-I'll give you a whole piece.
-Should I open my mouth?

223
00:08:23,936 --> 00:08:24,937
Please do.

224
00:08:25,004 --> 00:08:26,539
YUPDDUK

225
00:08:26,606 --> 00:08:28,708
It's as if we're watching
<i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

226
00:08:28,774 --> 00:08:30,209
A FAMILIAR SCENE

227
00:08:31,444 --> 00:08:32,812
He ate it.

228
00:08:32,879 --> 00:08:34,380
TASTING CAREFULLY

229
00:08:34,447 --> 00:08:36,549
-Will he get it?
-Can you guess it right?

230
00:08:36,616 --> 00:08:37,917
It's spicy.

231
00:08:38,484 --> 00:08:40,419
-It must be.
-It's spicy?

232
00:08:40,486 --> 00:08:43,890
It's not even a multiple-choice quiz,
so it must be hard to guess.

233
00:08:44,390 --> 00:08:46,926
-I'll guess after I try everything.
-Okay. The next one.

234
00:08:46,993 --> 00:08:48,661
-I have it here.
-The second place.

235
00:08:48,728 --> 00:08:49,729
SINTOBURI TTEOKBOKKI

236
00:08:49,795 --> 00:08:51,430
Why did you get it on his face?

237
00:08:51,497 --> 00:08:53,966
-It was too big.
-Wait a second.

238
00:08:54,300 --> 00:08:56,536
THE KIND-HEARTED GUY WIPES HIS LIPS

239
00:08:57,036 --> 00:08:58,838
NODS WITH CERTAINTY AFTER ONE BITE

240
00:08:58,905 --> 00:09:00,473
He can tell that easily?

241
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:02,174
-How does he know?
-This is…

242
00:09:02,241 --> 00:09:05,411
HE GETS IT TO-GO FROM HIS FAVORITE JOINT
AND EVEN FREEZES IT

243
00:09:05,978 --> 00:09:07,647
I've had this hundreds of times.

244
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:09,482
You can tell us if you're sure.

245
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:11,450
This is Sintoburi.

246
00:09:11,517 --> 00:09:14,253
-Sintoburi. Near Achasan, right?
-He's right.

247
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:15,922
He guessed the second one.

248
00:09:15,988 --> 00:09:18,491
I've had this dozens,
no, hundreds of times.

249
00:09:18,558 --> 00:09:20,426
Not even dozens. Hundreds of times.

250
00:09:20,493 --> 00:09:22,094
-You might not know the next one.
-Next one is hard.

251
00:09:22,161 --> 00:09:25,097
Now, the third one.
He already answered the second one.

252
00:09:25,431 --> 00:09:26,933
PICKS UP TWO PIECES LIKE IT'S ONE

253
00:09:26,999 --> 00:09:29,402
Now, the third place.

254
00:09:29,468 --> 00:09:30,903
The second one must be spicy too.

255
00:09:30,970 --> 00:09:32,004
It's a little big.

256
00:09:32,905 --> 00:09:34,974
-Why do you keep getting it on his face?
-I can't see

257
00:09:35,041 --> 00:09:36,776
-the other side.
-The third one.

258
00:09:37,476 --> 00:09:38,678
The third.

259
00:09:38,744 --> 00:09:40,947
UNSURE, SAVORS IT SLOWLY

260
00:09:41,013 --> 00:09:42,014
This is hard.

261
00:09:42,081 --> 00:09:43,249
-It must be.
-It's a hard one.

262
00:09:43,316 --> 00:09:46,686
We'll have to show him respect
if he gets this one right.

263
00:09:46,752 --> 00:09:48,254
Did you give me one piece of <i>tteok</i>?

264
00:09:50,356 --> 00:09:51,557
Was it two?

265
00:09:52,658 --> 00:09:53,893
SHH!

266
00:09:53,960 --> 00:09:55,428
He might be able to tell by its size.

267
00:09:55,494 --> 00:09:57,763
-I see. Because he likes it.
-Yes, right.

268
00:09:57,830 --> 00:09:59,065
I made them the same size.

269
00:09:59,131 --> 00:10:00,466
-Into the same size?
-Yes.

270
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:04,103
-The last one.
-He could tell by the gochujang sauce.

271
00:10:04,170 --> 00:10:05,705
My tongue is getting numb.

272
00:10:05,771 --> 00:10:06,806
-Of course.
-The last one.

273
00:10:06,872 --> 00:10:08,608
-Here we go.
-Try it now.

274
00:10:08,674 --> 00:10:09,842
-Open up.
-The last one.

275
00:10:11,377 --> 00:10:12,378
It looks good.

276
00:10:13,012 --> 00:10:16,682
-He only guessed the second one.
-He did.

277
00:10:16,749 --> 00:10:18,851
He hasn't guessed
the first, the third, and the fourth.

278
00:10:18,918 --> 00:10:20,419
-I see.
-Yes?

279
00:10:20,486 --> 00:10:22,088
You gave me something I would know.

280
00:10:22,154 --> 00:10:23,656
-Something you'd know?
-Do you know?

281
00:10:23,723 --> 00:10:24,724
Do you know?

282
00:10:25,591 --> 00:10:27,693
-Jopok Topokki.
-Jopok, Hongdae.

283
00:10:27,760 --> 00:10:28,761
AMAZED!

284
00:10:28,828 --> 00:10:30,997
-The fourth one.
-That's amazing.

285
00:10:32,331 --> 00:10:35,835
He guessed the second
and the fourth ones with certainty.

286
00:10:35,901 --> 00:10:37,169
-The first one…
-The first one.

287
00:10:37,236 --> 00:10:38,971
I think I know.

288
00:10:39,038 --> 00:10:41,240
I remember how painful it was
when I first had it.

289
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:43,242
-This is probably Yupdduk.
-Yupdduk.

290
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:46,479
Yupdduk.
His guess for the first one is Yupdduk.

291
00:10:46,545 --> 00:10:49,081
-Number three.
-The third one

292
00:10:49,148 --> 00:10:51,684
had a particular texture of <i>tteok</i>.

293
00:10:51,751 --> 00:10:54,553
-I actually order this one often.
-I see.

294
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:56,288
-I think he'll get it right.
-Yes.

295
00:10:56,355 --> 00:10:59,191
-Jaws.
-Jaws. Jaws?

296
00:11:00,292 --> 00:11:01,761
Jaws Tteokbokki?

297
00:11:01,827 --> 00:11:04,130
Yes, I eat their <i>tteokbokki</i> quite often.

298
00:11:04,196 --> 00:11:06,198
-It's a bit less spicy than I remember.
-This makes no sense.

299
00:11:06,265 --> 00:11:08,034
-This is crazy.
-Was that the case?

300
00:11:08,100 --> 00:11:11,537
But the chew of the <i>tteok</i>
seemed like Jaws Tteokbokki.

301
00:11:11,604 --> 00:11:13,005
-Let's find out the result.
-The result.

302
00:11:13,072 --> 00:11:15,007
-How did he do?
-The result.

303
00:11:15,074 --> 00:11:16,075
How did he do?

304
00:11:17,343 --> 00:11:19,111
He got everything right.

305
00:11:19,712 --> 00:11:23,082
EVEN HE'S MOVED BY HIS PERFORMANCE

306
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:25,217
THAT'S AMAZING

307
00:11:25,951 --> 00:11:27,553
-My gosh!
-How did you get this right?

308
00:11:27,620 --> 00:11:29,422
-How did you get it all?
-They were all cold too.

309
00:11:29,488 --> 00:11:30,756
You got nothing wrong.

310
00:11:30,823 --> 00:11:33,192
-This is crazy. Let's give it to him.
-You look surprised too.

311
00:11:33,659 --> 00:11:35,828
EVEN HE'S AMAZED WITH HIMSELF

312
00:11:35,895 --> 00:11:37,863
-<i>Tteokbokki</i>…
-You gave me two pieces of Jaws, right?

313
00:11:37,930 --> 00:11:39,198
-I did.
-Yes.

314
00:11:39,265 --> 00:11:41,467
-Because of the size.
-The size is different.

315
00:11:41,534 --> 00:11:42,802
SAW THROUGH THE TRICK

316
00:11:42,868 --> 00:11:45,337
Kyuhyun is, indeed, the <i>tteokbokki</i> master!

317
00:11:45,671 --> 00:11:48,674
KYUHYUN THE TTEOKBOKKI MASTER

318
00:11:49,975 --> 00:11:51,343
He would've been a chef if he didn't sing.

319
00:11:51,410 --> 00:11:52,678
-All right.
-Respect.

320
00:11:52,745 --> 00:11:55,081
Kyuhyun is someone
who's serious about cooking,

321
00:11:55,147 --> 00:11:57,717
so let's find out
what he brought in his fridge.

322
00:11:57,783 --> 00:11:59,251
Do you use it alone?

323
00:11:59,318 --> 00:12:01,387
Yes, it's 100% Kyuhyun's stuff.

324
00:12:01,454 --> 00:12:02,822
From what I hear,

325
00:12:02,888 --> 00:12:05,324
you have a total of six fridges at home.

326
00:12:05,591 --> 00:12:07,193
REALLY?

327
00:12:07,259 --> 00:12:09,228
-Six?
-Is that necessary at home?

328
00:12:09,295 --> 00:12:10,563
There's a story behind it.

329
00:12:10,629 --> 00:12:12,865
I lived in the dorm for 18 years,

330
00:12:12,932 --> 00:12:15,901
<i>so I brought the fridge I used there</i>
<i>when I moved out.</i>

331
00:12:15,968 --> 00:12:18,838
And when I moved,
I bought a bigger fridge to use every day.

332
00:12:18,904 --> 00:12:20,740
But at home,
there was already a built-in fridge

333
00:12:20,806 --> 00:12:22,575
and a wine cellar.

334
00:12:22,641 --> 00:12:24,910
Then someone gave me
another wine cellar as a present.

335
00:12:24,977 --> 00:12:27,680
<i>Lastly, thanks to my YouTube channel,</i>
<i>I got one sponsored.</i>

336
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:30,216
That's why I have six now.

337
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:31,650
NOT A PAUSED SCREEN

338
00:12:31,717 --> 00:12:34,754
This is why he was offered a spot
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

339
00:12:34,820 --> 00:12:36,655
I'm sure you want to see
what he has inside.

340
00:12:36,722 --> 00:12:40,659
You put everything
in one of the six fridges you have.

341
00:12:40,726 --> 00:12:43,596
-That's the everyday fridge.
-The everyday fridge. I see.

342
00:12:43,662 --> 00:12:45,431
Let's find out what he has.

343
00:12:45,498 --> 00:12:47,733
-We present Kyuhyun's fridge!
-Fridge!

344
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:49,568
WHOA

345
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:52,037
We're in paradise.

346
00:12:52,404 --> 00:12:54,540
PRESENTING KYUHYUN'S FRIDGE

347
00:12:55,407 --> 00:12:56,976
We're in paradise.

348
00:12:57,042 --> 00:12:59,111
FILLED TO THE BRIM

349
00:12:59,178 --> 00:13:00,279
He's pretty much a chef.

350
00:13:00,346 --> 00:13:03,849
It does seem like
he has professional ingredients like one.

351
00:13:03,916 --> 00:13:05,284
-He has lots of stuff.
-Yes.

352
00:13:05,351 --> 00:13:07,353
He's more of a chef than us.
We don't live like that.

353
00:13:07,419 --> 00:13:11,757
-I couldn't bring everything I had.
-You couldn't?

354
00:13:11,824 --> 00:13:12,858
That's about half.

355
00:13:13,592 --> 00:13:15,728
Let's look at the top shelf.

356
00:13:15,795 --> 00:13:17,263
Lard.

357
00:13:17,329 --> 00:13:20,232
-You have lard?
-"Lard, made with Korean pork fat."

358
00:13:20,299 --> 00:13:21,300
That's a good one.

359
00:13:21,367 --> 00:13:22,735
-What's this?
-Pork fat.

360
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:24,503
-At a regular household?
-It's unusual.

361
00:13:24,570 --> 00:13:26,672
-It's so good.
-I use it to make <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

362
00:13:26,739 --> 00:13:29,508
-Of course.
-I make dry <i>jjajangmyeon</i> with it.

363
00:13:29,575 --> 00:13:31,310
I watch recipes on YouTube,

364
00:13:31,377 --> 00:13:33,279
and people say
it tastes much better with lard.

365
00:13:33,345 --> 00:13:35,481
-That's true.
-I heard actual Chinese restaurants

366
00:13:35,548 --> 00:13:37,116
make <i>jjajangmyeon</i> with lard,

367
00:13:37,183 --> 00:13:39,185
-so I tried using it…
-Yes, we use lard.

368
00:13:39,251 --> 00:13:41,520
…and it really tasted different.

369
00:13:41,587 --> 00:13:44,256
I throw it out when it expires
and always keep a fresh one at home.

370
00:13:44,323 --> 00:13:45,724
MADE BY KYUHYUN

371
00:13:45,791 --> 00:13:47,793
-Do you like Chinese cuisine?
-I love it.

372
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:50,196
I've never seen someone
who makes that at home.

373
00:13:50,462 --> 00:13:52,364
I SEE WHY HE GOT AN OFFER TO BE ON CCW

374
00:13:52,431 --> 00:13:54,800
I just have the ingredients. That's all.

375
00:13:54,867 --> 00:13:56,235
He can probably fight Poong.

376
00:13:56,535 --> 00:13:58,671
KIM POONG
THE SHOW'S OFFICIAL TALENT TESTER

377
00:13:58,737 --> 00:14:01,207
Sausage. You have a few of these.

378
00:14:01,273 --> 00:14:03,275
I really love <i>budae-jjigae</i>, army stew.

379
00:14:03,342 --> 00:14:05,044
-Yes, <i>budae-jjigae</i>.
-That sounds good.

380
00:14:05,110 --> 00:14:06,979
-I eat it at least once a week.
-<i>Budae-jjigae</i>?

381
00:14:07,046 --> 00:14:08,981
At times, I make it at home,

382
00:14:09,048 --> 00:14:11,250
and it feels like it's bad for you, right?

383
00:14:11,317 --> 00:14:14,320
So I try to make it healthier
by using chicken breast ham

384
00:14:14,386 --> 00:14:16,522
and low-sugar ingredients.

385
00:14:16,589 --> 00:14:18,524
But I couldn't give up on that sausage.

386
00:14:18,591 --> 00:14:20,860
I'm not sure if I can share the brand,
but it's C brand.

387
00:14:20,926 --> 00:14:22,828
-It's a must. It has to be salty.
-It's something

388
00:14:22,895 --> 00:14:25,698
-used at <i>budae-jjigae</i> restaurants.
-It's the old one, right?

389
00:14:25,764 --> 00:14:28,067
-You can't eat it as is. It's too salty.
-It's salty.

390
00:14:28,133 --> 00:14:29,168
It's overly salty,

391
00:14:29,235 --> 00:14:30,469
but the moment it goes in water,

392
00:14:31,170 --> 00:14:32,538
it becomes perfect.

393
00:14:32,605 --> 00:14:34,740
-So this acts as seasoning too?
-Yes.

394
00:14:34,807 --> 00:14:37,610
-<i>Budae-jjigae</i>.
-He doesn't use any old sausage.

395
00:14:37,910 --> 00:14:39,612
HEY

396
00:14:40,179 --> 00:14:42,214
Don't you know it, Sung-ju and Jung-hwan?

397
00:14:42,281 --> 00:14:44,950
We called it the US Army sausage
when we were kids.

398
00:14:47,119 --> 00:14:48,287
We don't know.

399
00:14:48,354 --> 00:14:49,388
Stop lying!

400
00:14:49,455 --> 00:14:52,725
-You went to the US Army base?
-Only those who drove tanks know!

401
00:14:52,791 --> 00:14:55,895
-Did you chase after the tanks?
-It's that salty sausage.

402
00:14:55,961 --> 00:14:58,163
Saying, "Give me chocolate."

403
00:14:58,230 --> 00:15:00,399
We'd get that salty sausage
from the US Army base

404
00:15:00,466 --> 00:15:02,167
and share it with people.

405
00:15:02,234 --> 00:15:04,436
-You lived through that era.
-The original stew.

406
00:15:04,503 --> 00:15:06,472
I don't know what happened
in the US Army base.

407
00:15:06,538 --> 00:15:08,807
-There's something extraordinary.
-What is it?

408
00:15:08,874 --> 00:15:10,809
It looks like he makes desserts at home.

409
00:15:10,876 --> 00:15:12,611
Look at the green thing on the left.

410
00:15:12,678 --> 00:15:14,880
-H cream?
-Yes, H cream.

411
00:15:14,947 --> 00:15:16,048
-What's this?
-What is it?

412
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:17,983
-Whipping cream.
-It's whipping cream.

413
00:15:18,050 --> 00:15:19,818
I use it like fresh cream.

414
00:15:19,885 --> 00:15:22,087
-<i>As whipping cream?</i>
-<i>But I don't make desserts.</i>

415
00:15:22,154 --> 00:15:23,956
When I make Western cuisine, like pasta,

416
00:15:24,023 --> 00:15:25,858
-Really?
-I use it as a fresh cream substitute.

417
00:15:25,925 --> 00:15:29,361
-It doesn't expire for a while.
-It's shelf-stable.

418
00:15:29,428 --> 00:15:31,196
I really love Western cuisine.

419
00:15:31,263 --> 00:15:33,299
-You love it?
-I really do.

420
00:15:33,365 --> 00:15:35,334
Do you cook all three meals for yourself?

421
00:15:35,401 --> 00:15:36,936
Yes, I rarely get food delivered.

422
00:15:37,002 --> 00:15:38,304
-Whoa.
-Really?

423
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:39,972
I sometimes order <i>tteokbokki</i>.

424
00:15:40,039 --> 00:15:43,008
-He usually cooks for himself.
-At home.

425
00:15:43,075 --> 00:15:46,345
Let's go down another shelf.
What are these?

426
00:15:46,412 --> 00:15:49,148
-Is this Japanese? What's this?
-What is it?

427
00:15:49,214 --> 00:15:52,751
Those went viral, so I got intrigued
and bought them when I went to Japan.

428
00:15:52,818 --> 00:15:54,219
<i>All you have to do is put pork in</i>

429
00:15:54,887 --> 00:15:57,089
<i>and microwave the whole thing</i>
<i>to make soy-braised pork.</i>

430
00:15:57,456 --> 00:15:58,457
SHOCKING NEW CULTURE

431
00:15:58,524 --> 00:16:00,359
-Is it just the sauce?
-Just the sauce.

432
00:16:00,426 --> 00:16:02,962
-All you have to do is throw the pork in.
-I see.

433
00:16:03,028 --> 00:16:06,498
It went viral, and I fell for it,
but I haven't tried it yet.

434
00:16:06,565 --> 00:16:09,635
Look at how these ingredients
are prepped into small portions.

435
00:16:09,702 --> 00:16:11,036
-You did it yourself, right?
-Yes.

436
00:16:11,103 --> 00:16:12,571
There's a label. "Green onion."

437
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:14,640
"Onion." I see.

438
00:16:14,707 --> 00:16:16,608
And look at the veggies.

439
00:16:16,675 --> 00:16:19,378
It's like something you'll find
at an ordinary household.

440
00:16:19,445 --> 00:16:20,746
-To keep from drying.
-Yes.

441
00:16:20,813 --> 00:16:23,182
You don't have too many fruits.

442
00:16:23,248 --> 00:16:25,551
-Just one or two.
-I see.

443
00:16:25,617 --> 00:16:28,253
I'm trying to keep my sugar intake low.

444
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:30,255
-That's the trend.
-So no fruits?

445
00:16:30,322 --> 00:16:31,857
Those are leftovers

446
00:16:31,924 --> 00:16:34,593
from the fruit I gave away
after getting some at the office

447
00:16:34,660 --> 00:16:35,794
as a holiday present.

448
00:16:36,128 --> 00:16:37,930
THE IDOL STAR MUST STAY ON A DIET

449
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:40,199
These are the sauces. <i>Doubanjiang.</i>

450
00:16:40,499 --> 00:16:41,533
MANY FOREIGN SAUCES

451
00:16:41,600 --> 00:16:43,268
What's this?

452
00:16:43,335 --> 00:16:44,903
-Lao Gan Ma.
-Lao Gan Ma?

453
00:16:44,970 --> 00:16:46,071
Yes, Lao Gan Ma.

454
00:16:46,138 --> 00:16:48,173
A TYPE OF CHILI SAUCE
MADE WITH CHILI OIL, MEAT, CONDIMENTS

455
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:50,376
-He said he likes Chinese food.
-He really does.

456
00:16:50,442 --> 00:16:51,710
I wanted to make a dish

457
00:16:51,777 --> 00:16:54,747
called Fly's Head,
something I had in Taiwan.

458
00:16:54,813 --> 00:16:55,914
So I got that and made it,

459
00:16:55,981 --> 00:16:59,118
-but it was hard to wash the dishes later.
-He's right.

460
00:16:59,184 --> 00:17:00,819
-It's oily.
-Is it?

461
00:17:00,886 --> 00:17:02,554
I got scared, thinking how much oil I had.

462
00:17:02,621 --> 00:17:04,156
What if it stays inside forever?

463
00:17:04,223 --> 00:17:05,991
What if it doesn't go out of the system?

464
00:17:06,425 --> 00:17:08,127
NOT SCIENTIFICALLY PROVEN,
BUT JUST AN OPINION

465
00:17:08,193 --> 00:17:10,896
-You couldn't wash it off the dishes.
-The dish soap was no good.

466
00:17:10,963 --> 00:17:12,765
What if it stays in my system?

467
00:17:12,831 --> 00:17:14,867
So I've been scared of it
ever since that time.

468
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:16,635
Do you have a tip for doing the dishes

469
00:17:16,702 --> 00:17:18,604
-a little easier?
-A personal tip.

470
00:17:18,670 --> 00:17:20,239
-A tip?
-How do you wash it off?

471
00:17:20,305 --> 00:17:23,208
It's easy to wash off
if you use lots of dish soap in hot water.

472
00:17:23,709 --> 00:17:25,911
-Just use lots of dish soap.
-I see.

473
00:17:26,245 --> 00:17:28,380
"IF IT'S HARD TO CLEAN, USE LOTS OF SOAP"
AMY PARK

474
00:17:28,447 --> 00:17:29,815
Use lots of dish soap.

475
00:17:29,882 --> 00:17:31,617
Goodness.

476
00:17:33,052 --> 00:17:34,720
A BIG BOTTLE

477
00:17:34,787 --> 00:17:37,289
-He got the biggest bottle.
-The first time on the show.

478
00:17:37,356 --> 00:17:40,492
-How many liters does this hold?
-That's so big.

479
00:17:40,559 --> 00:17:42,027
It's 1.8 liters.

480
00:17:42,094 --> 00:17:43,328
It's not for drinking.

481
00:17:43,395 --> 00:17:46,799
I use it to cook
whenever I need some soju.

482
00:17:46,865 --> 00:17:49,835
One of his nicknames is Drunk Cho.

483
00:17:49,902 --> 00:17:51,970
-This is whiskey.
-Yes.

484
00:17:52,304 --> 00:17:53,672
THE DRINKER ALSO HAS WHISKEY

485
00:17:53,739 --> 00:17:55,174
You must be into this recently.

486
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:57,810
I rarely drink outside,
so I usually drink at home with friends,

487
00:17:57,876 --> 00:17:59,711
because I also love to cook.

488
00:17:59,778 --> 00:18:02,281
When my friends come over,
I pull out everything for them

489
00:18:02,347 --> 00:18:05,551
and even make cocktails like highballs
for them to enjoy.

490
00:18:05,617 --> 00:18:08,520
We took pictures of the alcohol
he keeps in his coolers.

491
00:18:08,587 --> 00:18:10,355
-Let's take a look.
-I want to see it.

492
00:18:10,422 --> 00:18:12,758
-Kyuhyun's home.
-This may cause a misunderstanding.

493
00:18:16,962 --> 00:18:18,530
<i>Is this a liquor store?</i>

494
00:18:18,597 --> 00:18:19,898
-Japanese whiskey.
-That's a lot.

495
00:18:19,965 --> 00:18:21,300
-All lines of Yamazaki.
-Yamazaki.

496
00:18:21,366 --> 00:18:22,534
-Twelve years.
-That's a lot.

497
00:18:22,601 --> 00:18:24,403
I don't drink everything there.

498
00:18:24,470 --> 00:18:26,605
DO NOT MISUNDERSTAND! IT'S HIS COLLECTION

499
00:18:26,672 --> 00:18:28,740
-Do you enjoy collecting these?
-Yes.

500
00:18:28,807 --> 00:18:30,542
What do you eat with your drinks?

501
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:32,010
At times, with <i>tteokbokki</i>.

502
00:18:32,077 --> 00:18:33,745
It goes rather well with whiskey.

503
00:18:33,812 --> 00:18:35,114
He's a big drinker.

504
00:18:35,180 --> 00:18:36,748
Do you also make <i>tteokbokki</i> at home?

505
00:18:36,815 --> 00:18:38,016
Of course.

506
00:18:38,083 --> 00:18:39,718
You do? You must have the ingredients.

507
00:18:39,785 --> 00:18:43,155
-I see. You have meal kits.
-At times, I use them.

508
00:18:43,222 --> 00:18:44,857
He has all these.

509
00:18:44,923 --> 00:18:47,092
Wait, you have more. Soupy <i>tteokbokki</i>.

510
00:18:47,159 --> 00:18:49,461
-And these.
-There they are. <i>Tteokbokki</i> ingredients.

511
00:18:49,528 --> 00:18:52,231
-Fish cakes.
-He has fish cakes here too.

512
00:18:52,297 --> 00:18:53,332
This is amazing.

513
00:18:53,398 --> 00:18:54,733
-And <i>sundae</i>, Korean sausage.
-<i>Sundae</i>.

514
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:56,935
THE BEST COMBINATION,
TTEOKBOKKI AND SUNDAE

515
00:18:57,002 --> 00:18:58,637
Do you steam this at home?

516
00:18:58,704 --> 00:19:00,672
I see lots of fritters in the space below.

517
00:19:00,739 --> 00:19:02,274
Why do you have so many of these?

518
00:19:02,341 --> 00:19:03,809
He must need them to eat with <i>tteokbokki</i>.

519
00:19:03,876 --> 00:19:05,177
That's a must.

520
00:19:06,178 --> 00:19:07,946
Perilla leaf fritters.

521
00:19:08,013 --> 00:19:09,848
He has perilla leaf fritters?

522
00:19:09,915 --> 00:19:11,550
-Chicken skin rolls.
-It's like a snack bar.

523
00:19:11,617 --> 00:19:13,018
I can't believe this.

524
00:19:13,085 --> 00:19:15,487
-Dumplings.
-Sweet potato fritters.

525
00:19:15,554 --> 00:19:16,555
You have so many of these.

526
00:19:16,622 --> 00:19:19,124
Yes, I like them quite a lot.
I have to eat them with <i>tteokbokki</i>.

527
00:19:19,191 --> 00:19:22,161
He has noodles too.
He does have lots of fritters.

528
00:19:22,227 --> 00:19:25,097
-That's amazing.
-Nana looks quite confused.

529
00:19:25,164 --> 00:19:27,432
-"Does he not stay on a diet?"
-Wait.

530
00:19:27,499 --> 00:19:30,969
You said you didn't eat fruit
because of sugar, but the fritters…

531
00:19:31,036 --> 00:19:32,037
That's worse.

532
00:19:32,104 --> 00:19:33,338
-No fruit, but…
-Exactly.

533
00:19:33,405 --> 00:19:34,573
-Worse than fruits.
-Precisely.

534
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:37,676
-Just eat some fruit.
-What about your blood vessels?

535
00:19:37,743 --> 00:19:39,878
I avoid fruit to eat <i>tteokbokki</i> instead.

536
00:19:39,945 --> 00:19:42,814
What if you had to choose
between fruit or <i>tteokbokki</i>?

537
00:19:43,982 --> 00:19:45,217
Do you have to ask? Of course…

538
00:19:45,284 --> 00:19:47,052
-Is it <i>tteokbokki</i>?
-I've already made my choice.

539
00:19:47,119 --> 00:19:49,154
-Yes, right.
-Yes.

540
00:19:49,221 --> 00:19:50,355
I'm sorry. That was thoughtless.

541
00:19:51,623 --> 00:19:52,724
Your mistake.

542
00:19:52,791 --> 00:19:54,293
EVERYONE, SAY "YOUR MISTAKE"

543
00:19:54,359 --> 00:19:56,828
-Your mistake.
-He really loves <i>tteokbokki</i>.

544
00:19:56,895 --> 00:19:58,330
Do you also enjoy seafood?

545
00:19:58,397 --> 00:20:00,999
Squid, crab, fish…

546
00:20:01,066 --> 00:20:03,468
-He has so many ingredients.
-Boneless mackerel.

547
00:20:03,535 --> 00:20:06,238
I found some meats in this one.

548
00:20:06,305 --> 00:20:08,340
Korean brisket, thin pork belly.

549
00:20:08,407 --> 00:20:10,375
-I prefer meat to seafood.
-You do?

550
00:20:10,442 --> 00:20:12,277
-More than seafood?
-He prefers meat.

551
00:20:12,344 --> 00:20:14,046
Look at the labels.

552
00:20:14,112 --> 00:20:16,114
"Baked beans."

553
00:20:16,181 --> 00:20:17,950
-"Mozzarella cheese."
-Cheese.

554
00:20:18,016 --> 00:20:19,484
-He has so much food.
-Right.

555
00:20:19,551 --> 00:20:22,187
Even if you wash the container,
it can still smell like the food.

556
00:20:22,254 --> 00:20:24,356
-"Unsalted butter."
-I see.

557
00:20:24,423 --> 00:20:25,791
What did he do with this?

558
00:20:25,857 --> 00:20:27,326
Unsalted butter.

559
00:20:27,392 --> 00:20:28,393
Look at this.

560
00:20:28,460 --> 00:20:30,729
-Did you do this?
-Yes, I put paper between the pieces.

561
00:20:30,796 --> 00:20:32,297
-You cut this yourself?
-Yes.

562
00:20:32,364 --> 00:20:33,565
My gosh. He's so prepared.

563
00:20:33,632 --> 00:20:34,766
You have these on an empty stomach?

564
00:20:34,833 --> 00:20:36,868
-No.
-He probably cooks with it.

565
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:39,104
-Someone does that.
-Nana.

566
00:20:39,171 --> 00:20:40,272
May I take some?

567
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:42,808
SHARING GLADLY

568
00:20:42,874 --> 00:20:45,110
Look at this. He saved it for later use.

569
00:20:45,177 --> 00:20:46,545
That's tuna sauce.

570
00:20:46,612 --> 00:20:48,113
-Is that a cat snack?
-Tuna sauce?

571
00:20:48,380 --> 00:20:50,048
THE CAT GUY THINKS IT'S A CAT SNACK

572
00:20:51,149 --> 00:20:53,352
-Look at this. This one.
-Yes, that's what I'm saying.

573
00:20:53,418 --> 00:20:55,621
-Noodles in a sealed bag.
-To keep them from drying.

574
00:20:55,687 --> 00:20:57,522
HE KEEPS THE INGREDIENTS SAFELY

575
00:20:57,589 --> 00:20:59,524
-He's thrifty.
-He is.

576
00:20:59,591 --> 00:21:01,727
Room temperature ingredients.
Look at this.

577
00:21:01,793 --> 00:21:03,895
He keeps things sealed.

578
00:21:03,962 --> 00:21:06,431
FRUGALITY AT MAX LEVEL

579
00:21:06,498 --> 00:21:09,067
He doesn't even throw away
leftover MSG sticks.

580
00:21:09,134 --> 00:21:11,203
He must cook often.

581
00:21:11,270 --> 00:21:13,038
I see why <i>CCW</i> wanted him on the show.

582
00:21:13,105 --> 00:21:14,139
NODS

583
00:21:14,206 --> 00:21:17,542
-They probably knew what he was like.
-Yes.

584
00:21:17,609 --> 00:21:19,911
That's it for Kyuhyun's fridge!

585
00:21:20,479 --> 00:21:21,947
PLEASED

586
00:21:22,014 --> 00:21:25,617
Now, let's find out
what he'd like to order today.

587
00:21:25,684 --> 00:21:29,054
This is his first order.

588
00:21:29,588 --> 00:21:32,057
-Kyu Wants to Copy Your Recipe.
-"Kyu."

589
00:21:32,124 --> 00:21:34,159
-Kyu Wants to Copy Your Recipe.
-Kyu Wants to Copy Your Recipe.

590
00:21:34,226 --> 00:21:35,294
What do you mean by this?

591
00:21:35,360 --> 00:21:37,829
Whenever I watch the show,

592
00:21:37,896 --> 00:21:40,766
I find myself wanting to copy the recipes,

593
00:21:40,832 --> 00:21:43,402
but I find it hard to do
without the actual recipe.

594
00:21:43,468 --> 00:21:45,237
So if you tell me the recipe,

595
00:21:45,304 --> 00:21:48,573
I want to copy it down to the second
and make a perfect copycat dish.

596
00:21:48,640 --> 00:21:53,145
I made the order because I wanted to make
an exact copy of the chefs' dishes.

597
00:21:53,211 --> 00:21:55,781
That means as they cook,
they'll have to explain the process

598
00:21:55,847 --> 00:21:57,616
-and what they add.
-They should.

599
00:21:57,683 --> 00:22:00,085
-Is it possible in 15 minutes?
-They can.

600
00:22:00,152 --> 00:22:01,453
-They must.
-But they can do it.

601
00:22:01,753 --> 00:22:03,488
OF COURSE, WE CAN

602
00:22:03,555 --> 00:22:06,725
So he wants a step-by-step commentary
as you cook your dish.

603
00:22:06,792 --> 00:22:08,593
There's one more. The second order.

604
00:22:08,660 --> 00:22:10,362
-Perfect for Whis-Kyu.
-Perfect for Whis-Kyu.

605
00:22:10,429 --> 00:22:11,930
-I see.
-A dish to eat with whiskey.

606
00:22:11,997 --> 00:22:14,066
-A bar snack.
-A whiskey snack.

607
00:22:14,132 --> 00:22:17,035
I've become a whiskey fan
in the last five years,

608
00:22:17,102 --> 00:22:20,238
so it would be great
if you made a great snack for the drink.

609
00:22:20,305 --> 00:22:21,740
I'll want to copy this too.

610
00:22:21,807 --> 00:22:23,208
I see.

611
00:22:23,275 --> 00:22:26,511
There are Ho-young, Kang-rok,
Poong, and Jong-won left.

612
00:22:26,578 --> 00:22:28,914
It's been a while for Kang-rok,
so let's have him choose first.

613
00:22:28,980 --> 00:22:30,515
-As Hyun-suk's rescue?
-Yes, that too.

614
00:22:30,582 --> 00:22:33,085
But he's just been
sitting around watching today, right?

615
00:22:33,151 --> 00:22:34,286
Time to work.

616
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:35,887
IF YOU'RE HERE, YOU'RE HERE TO COOK

617
00:22:35,954 --> 00:22:39,124
-Time to cook.
-Yes, and he's the winner of <i>CCW</i>.

618
00:22:39,191 --> 00:22:41,493
-He's the champion right now.
-He needs to do this.

619
00:22:41,560 --> 00:22:43,795
-And he must take his plushie.
-Yes.

620
00:22:43,862 --> 00:22:47,065
-We'll give you a chance, Kang-rok.
-Okay.

621
00:22:47,132 --> 00:22:49,334
I can make snacks for whiskey,

622
00:22:49,401 --> 00:22:51,503
but I myself am a soju guy.

623
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:54,373
So I want to take the top round,

624
00:22:54,439 --> 00:22:56,408
-but must I explain?
-You must.

625
00:22:56,708 --> 00:22:58,710
YOU MUST MAKE COMMENTS

626
00:22:58,777 --> 00:23:00,278
It'll be over after he says a few words.

627
00:23:00,345 --> 00:23:02,914
Talking is much harder for him
than cooking.

628
00:23:02,981 --> 00:23:04,750
He's a soju guy,
so he wants to avoid whiskey,

629
00:23:04,816 --> 00:23:06,184
but he must talk in the first round.

630
00:23:06,251 --> 00:23:07,686
All I want…

631
00:23:07,753 --> 00:23:09,955
is… to find out
what your commentary will be like.

632
00:23:10,021 --> 00:23:11,156
-"Is."
-"Is."

633
00:23:11,223 --> 00:23:14,025
FOR THOSE OF YOU WHO HAVE FORGOTTEN …IS!

634
00:23:14,092 --> 00:23:17,529
I'll cut it whole
and leave the skin intact.

635
00:23:17,596 --> 00:23:19,765
The fluffiness will…

636
00:23:19,831 --> 00:23:21,733
RIGHT…

637
00:23:21,800 --> 00:23:22,801
…is!

638
00:23:22,868 --> 00:23:24,870
That's what I want to present.

639
00:23:24,936 --> 00:23:26,304
HIS PHOBIA OF TALKING MADE THE MOMENT

640
00:23:27,773 --> 00:23:29,074
The commentary… is!

641
00:23:29,141 --> 00:23:30,509
It's something I can do well.

642
00:23:30,575 --> 00:23:32,144
-I see.
-Yes, but?

643
00:23:32,210 --> 00:23:33,512
I may not finish the dish.

644
00:23:33,578 --> 00:23:34,746
-Right.
-Of course.

645
00:23:34,813 --> 00:23:36,381
-He can do one or the other.
-Just one.

646
00:23:36,448 --> 00:23:39,451
The microphone will pick up everything
even if you mumble softly.

647
00:23:39,518 --> 00:23:42,087
In that case,

648
00:23:42,154 --> 00:23:45,824
let me give you a new recipe
to add to the repertoire

649
00:23:45,891 --> 00:23:47,392
of your cooking life.

650
00:23:47,726 --> 00:23:49,561
OH REALLY?

651
00:23:49,928 --> 00:23:51,963
KANG-ROK IS A WHOLE DIFFERENT GUY NOW

652
00:23:52,030 --> 00:23:53,498
That's why he's the winner.

653
00:23:53,565 --> 00:23:55,133
I'VE BECOME BRAVER

654
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:58,437
Kang-rok has taken the first slot.

655
00:23:58,503 --> 00:24:01,039
Ho-young also did well back then,
so do you want another chance?

656
00:24:01,106 --> 00:24:02,507
-Are you up for it?
-<i>CCW2</i>.

657
00:24:02,574 --> 00:24:04,509
I've been running a YouTube channel,

658
00:24:04,576 --> 00:24:06,878
and many people copy the recipes
I share with them.

659
00:24:06,945 --> 00:24:08,146
-He does.
-Yes.

660
00:24:08,213 --> 00:24:11,116
-I tried a lot of them too.
-So I'll keep the recipe easy

661
00:24:11,183 --> 00:24:12,684
while making something delicious.

662
00:24:12,751 --> 00:24:14,085
I see.

663
00:24:14,152 --> 00:24:15,754
I've been watching his channel.

664
00:24:15,821 --> 00:24:17,889
-I see.
-Thank you.

665
00:24:17,956 --> 00:24:19,791
His spicy braised chicken is the best.

666
00:24:19,858 --> 00:24:22,794
That means you two don't get to choose.

667
00:24:22,861 --> 00:24:24,796
Jong-won and Poong
are placed automatically.

668
00:24:24,863 --> 00:24:26,164
It's Son-Poong again.

669
00:24:26,231 --> 00:24:28,233
-It's time.
-A whiskey snack.

670
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:29,534
-So this is how it's going to be.
-But first,

671
00:24:29,601 --> 00:24:31,536
Kyu Wants to Copy Your Recipe.

672
00:24:31,603 --> 00:24:35,240
Let us begin the round
between Kang-rok and Ho-young!

673
00:24:35,540 --> 00:24:38,143
THE ROUND BEGINS NOW

674
00:24:38,210 --> 00:24:42,247
<i>This is the first cook-off</i>
<i>played with Kyuhyun's ingredients.</i>

675
00:24:42,314 --> 00:24:44,382
A man who cannot stop braising,

676
00:24:44,449 --> 00:24:46,618
Mr. Braise, Chef Choi Kang-rok,

677
00:24:46,685 --> 00:24:48,653
versus a man who cannot stop dancing,

678
00:24:48,720 --> 00:24:52,090
Mr. Dance, Chef Jung Ho-young.

679
00:24:52,157 --> 00:24:54,059
-They're quite close, actually.
-Yes.

680
00:24:54,125 --> 00:24:56,394
And this is the round

681
00:24:56,461 --> 00:24:58,864
between first place and fourth place
of <i>CCW2</i>.

682
00:24:58,930 --> 00:25:00,866
I realized after watching that show

683
00:25:00,932 --> 00:25:04,135
that the more time Kang-rok gets,
the more advantageous he is.

684
00:25:04,202 --> 00:25:07,539
<i>I have 180 minutes anyway,</i>
<i>so I'll braise this to my heart's content.</i>

685
00:25:07,606 --> 00:25:08,940
HE BRAISED ALL HE WANTED THERE

686
00:25:09,207 --> 00:25:10,509
I hear they give three hours.

687
00:25:10,575 --> 00:25:12,310
-Did you get three hours?
-Really?

688
00:25:12,377 --> 00:25:14,112
Yes, I got 180 minutes.

689
00:25:14,179 --> 00:25:17,182
After only getting 15 minutes here,
that was really sweet.

690
00:25:18,283 --> 00:25:19,651
-So sweet!
-Three hours?

691
00:25:19,718 --> 00:25:22,254
I would step out
and go to a sauna during the round.

692
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:27,158
It's been a year since Chef Kang-rok
stood before the counter in this studio.

693
00:25:27,225 --> 00:25:28,527
How do you feel?

694
00:25:29,094 --> 00:25:31,162
I'm here as Hyun-suk's rescue,

695
00:25:31,229 --> 00:25:34,966
so my loss equals his loss.

696
00:25:36,468 --> 00:25:38,603
-That's true.
-He's free from responsibility.

697
00:25:38,670 --> 00:25:41,239
-I'm not too nervous today.
-He's right.

698
00:25:41,306 --> 00:25:45,277
Why don't you share a word of support?
After all, he's here as your rescue.

699
00:25:45,343 --> 00:25:47,846
There was something I said to him

700
00:25:47,913 --> 00:25:50,015
when he seemed dispirited on this show.

701
00:25:50,582 --> 00:25:52,417
"You may seem like a chick right now,

702
00:25:52,484 --> 00:25:54,286
but you're actually an eagle."

703
00:25:54,953 --> 00:25:57,856
"I know you will fly high above the sky."

704
00:25:57,923 --> 00:26:00,258
And as you can see,
he has spread his wings, right?

705
00:26:00,325 --> 00:26:02,193
-You said that?
-Do not mind anybody

706
00:26:02,260 --> 00:26:04,663
-and focus on your--
-I never heard that.

707
00:26:04,729 --> 00:26:08,266
Why are you talking over me
while I'm saying something important?

708
00:26:08,333 --> 00:26:09,868
I was talking to myself.

709
00:26:09,935 --> 00:26:12,871
-He said that? Did he really?
-I did.

710
00:26:12,938 --> 00:26:14,773
My nickname is Bald Eagle.

711
00:26:14,839 --> 00:26:16,274
BECAUSE OF WHAT YOU SAID

