1437
00:53:19,429 --> 00:53:21,798
And next, the fourth place of <i>CCW2</i>,

1438
00:53:21,865 --> 00:53:23,500
<i>Chef Jung Ho-young's dish.</i>

1439
00:53:23,567 --> 00:53:26,036
LOOKING TO SELLOUT WITH A DEEP-FRIED DISH

1440
00:53:27,204 --> 00:53:30,674
JAPANESE-STYLE CORN FRITTERS
AND CHINESE SICHUAN SWEET AND SOUR BEEF

1441
00:53:31,174 --> 00:53:34,678
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
KANG-ROK, SORRY, SORRY

1442
00:53:35,245 --> 00:53:36,846
-That looks good too.
-Yes.

1443
00:53:36,913 --> 00:53:38,014
What should he begin with?

1444
00:53:38,081 --> 00:53:40,283
Try the corn fritter first.

1445
00:53:40,350 --> 00:53:41,851
-It smells good.
-It does.

1446
00:53:41,918 --> 00:53:43,853
It's not easy to deep-fry food at home.

1447
00:53:43,920 --> 00:53:45,455
-No.
-But Chef Ho-young showed

1448
00:53:45,522 --> 00:53:47,190
the true essence of deep-fried food.

1449
00:53:47,624 --> 00:53:49,259
A BITE OF CORN FRITTER

1450
00:53:49,326 --> 00:53:50,927
That'd be perfect with beer.

1451
00:53:50,994 --> 00:53:53,496
Kyuhyun already loves fritters.

1452
00:53:54,331 --> 00:53:56,233
He's had numerous deep-fried foods before.

1453
00:53:56,299 --> 00:53:57,367
He's glaring again.

1454
00:53:57,934 --> 00:53:59,269
After eating only frozen fritters,

1455
00:53:59,336 --> 00:54:01,137
I finally feel like
I'm having a real fritter.

1456
00:54:02,439 --> 00:54:05,442
It's so delicious
and seasoned perfectly too.

1457
00:54:05,508 --> 00:54:07,043
SEASONING, FLAVOR, TEXTURE, ALL GOOD

1458
00:54:07,110 --> 00:54:08,912
Next, the sweet and sour beef.

1459
00:54:08,979 --> 00:54:10,213
It's made with beef.

1460
00:54:10,780 --> 00:54:12,515
Jeez. That looks so good.

1461
00:54:14,985 --> 00:54:16,086
CRUNCHY

1462
00:54:16,152 --> 00:54:17,387
MMM!

1463
00:54:17,454 --> 00:54:18,755
What is it?

1464
00:54:18,822 --> 00:54:20,056
It must be good.

1465
00:54:20,123 --> 00:54:21,625
THINKING

1466
00:54:21,691 --> 00:54:24,094
-It has to be.
-That's guaranteed.

1467
00:54:24,961 --> 00:54:27,631
It almost tastes
like sweet and spicy beef.

1468
00:54:27,697 --> 00:54:29,399
Yes, I made a spicier version

1469
00:54:29,466 --> 00:54:31,901
to make the sauce recipe easier.

1470
00:54:31,968 --> 00:54:34,170
-The sauce is so good.
-Sichuan sweet and sour beef.

1471
00:54:34,237 --> 00:54:37,240
<i>It's Sichuan sweet and sour beef,</i>
<i>but it's also like sweet and spicy beef.</i>

1472
00:54:37,307 --> 00:54:39,476
But it's not too spicy.

1473
00:54:39,542 --> 00:54:41,144
It's sweet,

1474
00:54:41,211 --> 00:54:45,382
so it's somewhere between
the spicy sauce and the sour sauce.

1475
00:54:45,448 --> 00:54:47,250
I'll keep craving more.

1476
00:54:47,317 --> 00:54:50,053
We saw you making the sauce,
and it didn't seem too hard.

1477
00:54:50,120 --> 00:54:52,155
<i>Ketchup, vinegar, sugar,</i>

1478
00:54:52,222 --> 00:54:53,556
<i>Lao Gan Ma,</i>

1479
00:54:53,623 --> 00:54:56,293
<i>and cooking wine in the same ratio.</i>

1480
00:54:57,727 --> 00:55:01,031
The batter is amazing,
along with the sauce.

1481
00:55:01,097 --> 00:55:02,966
He shared the secrets
to deep-frying at home.

1482
00:55:03,033 --> 00:55:05,869
All right. Let's try
Chef Kang-rok's dish first.

1483
00:55:05,935 --> 00:55:07,337
-Okay.
-Chef Kang-rok's dish.

1484
00:55:07,404 --> 00:55:09,406
How good is it?

1485
00:55:09,839 --> 00:55:12,942
WHAT'S THE RAMYEON AND EGG SOUP LIKE?

1486
00:55:15,745 --> 00:55:17,547
This is so new.

1487
00:55:17,614 --> 00:55:18,815
-It's good.
-Interesting.

1488
00:55:22,519 --> 00:55:23,787
Gosh, this is…

1489
00:55:25,755 --> 00:55:27,624
It's kind of like Thai crab curry.

1490
00:55:27,691 --> 00:55:28,892
-Yes.
-Yes.

1491
00:55:28,958 --> 00:55:32,128
-It tastes like that. Thai crab curry.
-Thai crab curry.

1492
00:55:32,195 --> 00:55:33,229
I say it's Chinese.

1493
00:55:33,296 --> 00:55:34,864
-I agree.
-It's mostly Chinese.

1494
00:55:34,931 --> 00:55:36,399
It's because of the Lao Gan Ma.

1495
00:55:36,466 --> 00:55:39,002
You won't need to order <i>malatang</i>
if you can make this.

1496
00:55:39,069 --> 00:55:40,804
It tastes Chinese.

1497
00:55:40,870 --> 00:55:44,207
Chef Hyun-suk and I tried it
before the chili sauce, right?

1498
00:55:44,274 --> 00:55:45,842
-I liked that better.
-Me too.

1499
00:55:45,909 --> 00:55:47,977
I liked it much better without it.

1500
00:55:48,044 --> 00:55:50,914
-This is quite Chinese now.
-It's very Chinese.

1501
00:55:50,980 --> 00:55:53,550
Just like you mentioned,

1502
00:55:53,616 --> 00:55:55,085
-it's like curry.
-Thai crab curry.

1503
00:55:55,151 --> 00:55:58,221
The texture of the egg
is similar to crab meat.

1504
00:55:58,288 --> 00:56:01,691
It's like crab soup,
something really smooth.

1505
00:56:01,758 --> 00:56:06,196
He brought out the highest potential
that <i>ramyeon</i> has

1506
00:56:06,262 --> 00:56:09,399
and the highest potential that eggs have.

1507
00:56:09,466 --> 00:56:11,267
-That's why he's Kang-rok.
-It's Kang-rok.

1508
00:56:11,334 --> 00:56:13,036
Is that why he's Kang-rok?

1509
00:56:13,103 --> 00:56:14,304
This is such a winner.

1510
00:56:14,371 --> 00:56:17,574
In that case,
what's Chef Ho-young's dish like?

1511
00:56:17,640 --> 00:56:19,175
I love the corn fritter.

1512
00:56:20,076 --> 00:56:21,244
HAPPINESS

1513
00:56:21,311 --> 00:56:23,079
-No words needed.
-Not at all.

1514
00:56:23,146 --> 00:56:24,781
YUM

1515
00:56:24,848 --> 00:56:26,750
-It's good.
-Man.

1516
00:56:26,816 --> 00:56:28,651
It's even better after some rice.

1517
00:56:29,319 --> 00:56:30,987
The beef is really crispy.

1518
00:56:31,054 --> 00:56:33,890
I could eat the corn fritter forever.

1519
00:56:33,957 --> 00:56:35,692
AGREED
EVERYONE LOVES BOTH DEEP-FRIED DISHES

1520
00:56:35,759 --> 00:56:37,994
These two are so delicious too.

1521
00:56:38,061 --> 00:56:43,400
The chewy texture remained
inside the crispy coating.

1522
00:56:43,466 --> 00:56:45,034
It's like pork
fried in glutinous rice powder.

1523
00:56:45,101 --> 00:56:46,636
-Yes, it has that texture.
-Yes.

1524
00:56:46,703 --> 00:56:48,171
It's refreshing yet crispy.

1525
00:56:48,238 --> 00:56:50,907
-He's good at deep-frying.
-It doesn't make my mouth gritty.

1526
00:56:50,974 --> 00:56:54,511
Not a lot of people can hate this.

1527
00:56:54,577 --> 00:56:56,279
It's now time to decide.

1528
00:56:56,346 --> 00:56:58,281
Make your choice, Kyuhyun.

1529
00:56:58,348 --> 00:56:59,816
<i>Press one for Kang-rok.</i>

1530
00:57:00,717 --> 00:57:02,552
<i>Press two for Ho-young.</i>

1531
00:57:03,086 --> 00:57:06,222
Kyuhyun knows a thing or two about food,
and this is his choice.

1532
00:57:06,289 --> 00:57:08,591
Who did he choose?

1533
00:57:08,658 --> 00:57:10,960
Let's find out the result. Show us!

1534
00:57:11,027 --> 00:57:12,262
I wonder who it is.

1535
00:57:12,328 --> 00:57:14,998
Will Choi Kang-rok win a star
in this glorious return

1536
00:57:15,064 --> 00:57:17,467
after his victory in <i>CCW2</i>?

1537
00:57:17,534 --> 00:57:21,271
Or will Jung Ho-young,
the fixture of the show, take it?

1538
00:57:21,337 --> 00:57:24,274
Who did Kyuhyun choose?

1539
00:57:24,340 --> 00:57:26,543
Show us the winner!

1540
00:57:26,609 --> 00:57:27,811
Show us!

1541
00:57:28,645 --> 00:57:29,679
Who did Kyuhyun choose?

1542
00:57:29,746 --> 00:57:31,414
CHOI KANG-ROK WINS

1543
00:57:31,815 --> 00:57:33,216
JUST ONE DISH FOR YOU WINS

1544
00:57:33,283 --> 00:57:35,318
Kang-rok wins!

1545
00:57:35,385 --> 00:57:36,586
It goes to Kang-rok!

1546
00:57:36,920 --> 00:57:37,921
PROUD

1547
00:57:37,987 --> 00:57:39,823
-Kang-rok wins.
-He wins as soon as he returns.

1548
00:57:39,889 --> 00:57:42,659
-Kang-rok returned as a changed man.
-I knew it.

1549
00:57:42,725 --> 00:57:44,561
If I had to decide

1550
00:57:44,627 --> 00:57:48,331
only on the flavor,
then it could've been Chef Ho-young.

1551
00:57:48,398 --> 00:57:52,936
But I asked you to make something
that I could recreate at home.

1552
00:57:53,002 --> 00:57:56,473
But using starch and all the powder

1553
00:57:56,539 --> 00:57:59,442
-was too complicated for me.
-It's not easy to deep-fry at home.

1554
00:57:59,509 --> 00:58:00,844
Even Ho-young was lost.

1555
00:58:00,910 --> 00:58:03,313
<i>He went back and forth</i>
<i>trying to fix the thickness.</i>

1556
00:58:03,379 --> 00:58:05,181
It wouldn't be easy
to make the batter right.

1557
00:58:05,248 --> 00:58:09,853
So I ended up choosing a simpler recipe.

1558
00:58:09,919 --> 00:58:13,857
Also, while they cooked

1559
00:58:13,923 --> 00:58:15,892
and told me their recipes,

1560
00:58:15,959 --> 00:58:18,061
the way that he spoke

1561
00:58:18,127 --> 00:58:19,629
touched my heart.

1562
00:58:20,230 --> 00:58:23,533
He's now moving the guest's heart
with his words.

1563
00:58:23,600 --> 00:58:25,969
Your daughter's probably watching,
so say something to her.

1564
00:58:26,035 --> 00:58:27,237
You can take the plushie now.

1565
00:58:28,104 --> 00:58:29,272
I'll bring the plushie home.

1566
00:58:30,874 --> 00:58:32,141
"I'll bring the plushie home."

1567
00:58:32,208 --> 00:58:35,078
-Please put a star on Chef Kang-rok!
-Thank you.

1568
00:58:35,144 --> 00:58:37,447
-And you get the plushie!
-Congratulations!

1569
00:58:37,514 --> 00:58:38,882
-Gosh.
-The plushie for your girl.

1570
00:58:38,948 --> 00:58:41,050
Congratulations!

1571
00:58:41,117 --> 00:58:42,452
Choi Kang-rok!

1572
00:58:42,519 --> 00:58:44,554
LEAVING WITH FLUSHED EARS

1573
00:58:44,621 --> 00:58:46,089
<i>The second round of cook-off</i>

1574
00:58:46,155 --> 00:58:50,460
<i>for Kyuhyun, Gwanggaeto the Great</i>
<i>of the Korean Wave, with his ingredients.</i>

1575
00:58:50,527 --> 00:58:53,596
The king of fine dining,
Chef Son Jong-won,

1576
00:58:53,663 --> 00:58:57,500
is up against the king of wreckage dining,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1577
00:58:58,501 --> 00:59:00,603
Geez. He's so unsightly.

1578
00:59:00,670 --> 00:59:02,739
-"Unsightly"?
-"Unsightly"?

1579
00:59:02,805 --> 00:59:05,708
They recently received
the Best Couple Award.

1580
00:59:05,775 --> 00:59:07,043
DURING THE AWARDS EPISODE

1581
00:59:07,110 --> 00:59:12,048
But today, they must face one another
as enemies.

1582
00:59:12,115 --> 00:59:14,951
Are you two wearing the same apron?

1583
00:59:15,018 --> 00:59:16,286
-They're the same, right?
-Yes.

1584
00:59:16,352 --> 00:59:19,389
Same design, different fits.
That's the case.

1585
00:59:19,455 --> 00:59:20,823
-I think…
-Matching aprons.

1586
00:59:20,890 --> 00:59:22,258
…they became friends easily

1587
00:59:22,325 --> 00:59:24,961
because they rarely
fought against each other.

1588
00:59:25,028 --> 00:59:26,663
-That's a possibility.
-That's true.

1589
00:59:26,729 --> 00:59:30,300
It's their first round this year,
and even last year, they only fought once.

1590
00:59:30,366 --> 00:59:31,601
That's true.

1591
00:59:31,668 --> 00:59:33,937
And if I may add,
Poong won the first time.

1592
00:59:34,003 --> 00:59:36,139
-Do you remember that, Jong-won?
-Of course.

1593
00:59:36,205 --> 00:59:38,074
It's unforgettable, actually.

1594
00:59:38,141 --> 00:59:39,576
-Really?
-Wait.

1595
00:59:39,642 --> 00:59:42,478
-Just forget it. You're a busy man.
-He's sulky.

1596
00:59:42,779 --> 00:59:43,846
ONLY REMEMBER THE GOOD THINGS

1597
00:59:43,913 --> 00:59:47,317
Before we started the cook-off,
it was his wavy dance

1598
00:59:47,383 --> 00:59:48,651
that threw me off.

1599
00:59:49,185 --> 00:59:51,220
WAVY

1600
00:59:51,521 --> 00:59:52,589
FATAL

1601
00:59:52,655 --> 00:59:55,258
-My mind went blank.
-Back then.

1602
00:59:55,325 --> 00:59:57,760
-Back then, you were easily shaken.
-Yes.

1603
00:59:57,827 --> 00:59:59,228
My brain froze.

1604
00:59:59,862 --> 01:00:02,865
HERE'S ANOTHER LOOK AT IT

1605
01:00:03,099 --> 01:00:04,467
WHAT A SCENE

1606
01:00:04,534 --> 01:00:07,103
-Jong-won was alarmed to see him.
-He was.

1607
01:00:07,170 --> 01:00:12,208
But I heard you've been waiting
to fight Poong.

1608
01:00:12,275 --> 01:00:13,443
REALLY?

1609
01:00:13,509 --> 01:00:16,045
In my opinion, there's no one else

1610
01:00:16,112 --> 01:00:18,014
who understands and recognizes

1611
01:00:18,081 --> 01:00:20,049
-his food more than me.
-That's true.

1612
01:00:20,116 --> 01:00:21,618
But it wasn't mutual.

1613
01:00:21,684 --> 01:00:22,752
WHAT?

1614
01:00:22,819 --> 01:00:25,989
When he came as a guest,
he didn't choose me.

1615
01:00:26,589 --> 01:00:28,391
-He didn't.
-Wait!

1616
01:00:28,458 --> 01:00:29,759
-He remembers.
-Wait, that's…

1617
01:00:29,826 --> 01:00:31,995
You're still thinking of that?

1618
01:00:32,061 --> 01:00:33,529
They're finally falling apart.

1619
01:00:33,596 --> 01:00:37,567
There seems to be
a bit of a rift between them.

1620
01:00:37,634 --> 01:00:40,503
What about you, Poong?
How significant is this cook-off

1621
01:00:40,570 --> 01:00:42,305
against Jong-won for you?

1622
01:00:42,372 --> 01:00:44,240
To me, this is a moment

1623
01:00:44,307 --> 01:00:47,010
I've been waiting for.

1624
01:00:47,076 --> 01:00:50,413
Jong-won is the living vein of gold

1625
01:00:50,480 --> 01:00:52,515
in terms of cooking techniques.

1626
01:00:52,582 --> 01:00:54,384
I think this is a great opportunity

1627
01:00:54,450 --> 01:00:56,953
to pick up his skills from by his side.

1628
01:00:57,020 --> 01:01:00,757
He got here today
by stealing many techniques

1629
01:01:00,823 --> 01:01:02,291
-from a number of chefs.
-You're right.

1630
01:01:02,358 --> 01:01:04,360
What if he learns from Jong-won too?

1631
01:01:04,427 --> 01:01:06,295
-That's crazy.
-He stole Hyun-suk's <i>miyeok-guk</i>.

1632
01:01:06,362 --> 01:01:09,532
-He's like a straw that sucks everything.
-Isn't he?

1633
01:01:09,599 --> 01:01:12,568
What you'll have to make today
is a snack to pair with whiskey.

1634
01:01:12,635 --> 01:01:15,104
Actually, back in the day,

1635
01:01:15,171 --> 01:01:17,407
I was a part of a whiskey club,

1636
01:01:17,473 --> 01:01:19,942
so I've had a fair share
of experience in that world.

1637
01:01:20,009 --> 01:01:24,113
I probably have an advantage
because I know what goes well with it.

1638
01:01:24,180 --> 01:01:27,784
But we can't talk about whiskey
without mentioning Jong-won.

1639
01:01:27,850 --> 01:01:30,286
He was a whiskey brand's ambassador,

1640
01:01:30,353 --> 01:01:34,924
someone who stood next to Zo In-sung
and worked with him.

1641
01:01:34,991 --> 01:01:37,727
-You probably feel confident too.
-It suits him.

1642
01:01:37,794 --> 01:01:40,163
I had been an ambassador
for a whiskey brand,

1643
01:01:40,229 --> 01:01:43,332
and I also kept my eyes on Kyuhyun
right by his side.

1644
01:01:43,399 --> 01:01:45,334
So I think I can make a dish

1645
01:01:45,401 --> 01:01:47,470
that'll suit a successful
yet lonely man like him.

1646
01:01:47,537 --> 01:01:51,340
-"Successful yet lonely"?
-A successful yet lonely man.

1647
01:01:51,407 --> 01:01:53,476
-There's that vibe successful men have.
-Right.

1648
01:01:53,543 --> 01:01:55,645
-Wait, we received a tip.
-Yes?

1649
01:01:55,712 --> 01:01:58,114
Poong, you had been a model
for an alcohol brand too?

1650
01:01:58,181 --> 01:02:00,416
-Really?
-Which one was it?

1651
01:02:00,483 --> 01:02:01,884
Black raspberry wine.

1652
01:02:01,951 --> 01:02:03,286
It suits him.

1653
01:02:03,352 --> 01:02:05,354
-It's perfect.
-That sounds perfect for you.

1654
01:02:05,421 --> 01:02:08,624
-It's all about that power.
-He's a strong man.

1655
01:02:08,691 --> 01:02:11,828
Jong-won and whiskey,
Poong and black raspberry wine.

1656
01:02:11,894 --> 01:02:12,929
Both sound perfect.

1657
01:02:13,863 --> 01:02:15,865
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
CUCUMBER, TOMATO

1658
01:02:15,932 --> 01:02:17,934
BRISKET, BURRATA, TUNA SAUCE,
PEANUT BUTTER, LEMON JUICE

1659
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:20,136
The name of my dish is…

1660
01:02:20,203 --> 01:02:22,305
Chinese-ish Poong!

1661
01:02:22,371 --> 01:02:24,240
In the tone of "We're SUPER JUNIOR!"

1662
01:02:24,807 --> 01:02:27,410
-Chinese-ish Poong!
-Chinese-ish Poong!

1663
01:02:27,477 --> 01:02:31,547
You may hold to a prejudice that
Chinese food doesn't go well with whiskey.

1664
01:02:31,614 --> 01:02:34,984
But if the flavor isn't too extreme,
it goes quite well.

1665
01:02:35,051 --> 01:02:37,286
-Yes.
-I've had my share of whiskey,

1666
01:02:37,353 --> 01:02:39,589
so I already know what the best snack is

1667
01:02:39,655 --> 01:02:41,124
to eat with the drink.

1668
01:02:41,190 --> 01:02:42,692
-I see.
-I personally think

1669
01:02:42,759 --> 01:02:45,595
-it's cucumbers.
-Cucumbers?

1670
01:02:45,661 --> 01:02:46,763
Wait!

1671
01:02:47,864 --> 01:02:50,433
I often eat cucumbers with whiskey.

1672
01:02:50,500 --> 01:02:51,934
I see.

1673
01:02:52,001 --> 01:02:53,002
Bull's eye.

1674
01:02:53,069 --> 01:02:54,771
-Did you get lucky again?
-Yes.

1675
01:02:54,837 --> 01:02:55,872
"Again."

1676
01:02:55,938 --> 01:02:58,541
Nothing goes better with whiskey
than cucumbers.

1677
01:02:58,608 --> 01:03:01,844
So you can think of this
as a cold cucumber salad.

1678
01:03:01,911 --> 01:03:03,713
I'll also add brisket.

1679
01:03:03,780 --> 01:03:07,984
Once before,
Chef Jong-won used plastic wrap

1680
01:03:08,050 --> 01:03:11,954
<i>and rolled up avocado to make his dish.</i>

1681
01:03:12,021 --> 01:03:16,092
I'm going to use that technique
and make the cucumber look pretty.

1682
01:03:16,159 --> 01:03:17,794
There's another kick.

1683
01:03:17,860 --> 01:03:21,764
I'll add some smoky aroma to it.

1684
01:03:21,831 --> 01:03:24,133
-How? With wood smoke?
-How will you do that?

1685
01:03:24,867 --> 01:03:26,135
You'll see.

1686
01:03:26,202 --> 01:03:27,870
OMITS THE DETAILS

1687
01:03:28,704 --> 01:03:31,107
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
CUCUMBER, CARROT, ROMAINE

1688
01:03:31,174 --> 01:03:34,310
CABBAGE, NAPA CABBAGE, RED PEPPER,
POTATO, JEJU ORANGE, PEAR, AND MORE

1689
01:03:34,377 --> 01:03:37,747
The dish I'll make for Kyuhyun is…

1690
01:03:37,814 --> 01:03:40,716
Veggies are Perfect for Whis-Kyu.

1691
01:03:41,417 --> 01:03:44,720
-Veggies are Perfect for Whis-Kyu.
-Veggies are Perfect for Whis-Kyu.

1692
01:03:44,787 --> 01:03:46,088
Are you talking about cucumbers?

1693
01:03:46,155 --> 01:03:48,291
-They're included.
-Including cucumbers.

1694
01:03:48,357 --> 01:03:50,493
He seems to enjoy
the flavor and aroma of whiskey,

1695
01:03:50,560 --> 01:03:54,197
so I prepared many different veggie dishes
that would go well with it.

1696
01:03:54,263 --> 01:03:55,298
The key point

1697
01:03:55,364 --> 01:03:57,333
-is that you can copy the recipe.
-Really?

1698
01:03:57,400 --> 01:03:58,568
-I love it.
-I'll do that.

1699
01:03:58,634 --> 01:04:01,671
I'll serve two different dishes.
First, crudités.

1700
01:04:01,737 --> 01:04:05,208
It's a variety of veggies
you can dip in a sauce.

1701
01:04:05,274 --> 01:04:08,244
-I'll also make vegetable pot-au-feu.
-Pot-au-feu.

1702
01:04:08,311 --> 01:04:12,949
It's a soup dish, so it'll help you
digest alcohol as you drink.

1703
01:04:13,015 --> 01:04:15,618
Both dishes
are inspired by French cuisine.

1704
01:04:15,685 --> 01:04:18,421
French-style versus Chinese-style.

1705
01:04:18,487 --> 01:04:20,489
Let us begin the round.

1706
01:04:20,556 --> 01:04:21,791
All right, then.

1707
01:04:21,858 --> 01:04:25,695
The best couple now faces one another.

1708
01:04:25,761 --> 01:04:28,564
He came to get his revenge
against Poong today!

1709
01:04:28,631 --> 01:04:31,033
The incarnation of revenge,
Chef Son Jong-won!

1710
01:04:31,100 --> 01:04:34,203
He came to steal
every technique Jong-won has.

1711
01:04:34,270 --> 01:04:37,707
The incarnation of sticky fingers,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong!

1712
01:04:37,773 --> 01:04:41,510
Which one of them
will be chosen by Drunk Cho?

1713
01:04:41,577 --> 01:04:44,013
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1714
01:04:45,381 --> 01:04:46,382
Begin!

1715
01:04:46,449 --> 01:04:48,317
THE FIRST SON-POONG MATCH IN THE SEASON!

1716
01:04:48,384 --> 01:04:49,385
GREEN ONION

1717
01:04:49,452 --> 01:04:51,420
-Chili oil again?
-Chili oil?

1718
01:04:53,656 --> 01:04:54,991
The heat is too high.

1719
01:04:55,057 --> 01:04:57,226
-You should lower it.
-Be careful.

1720
01:04:57,293 --> 01:05:00,096
-He's making chili oil right away.
-It's chili oil.

1721
01:05:00,162 --> 01:05:03,633
-He always begins with chili oil.
-Always.

1722
01:05:03,699 --> 01:05:05,134
I'm reminded of this again.

1723
01:05:05,201 --> 01:05:07,370
When I asked,
"Why are all your dishes the same?"

1724
01:05:07,436 --> 01:05:09,472
He said, "Who cares? The guests change."

1725
01:05:11,874 --> 01:05:13,376
I've been curious about his dishes.

1726
01:05:13,442 --> 01:05:17,813
How good were his dishes
to win against chefs like them?

1727
01:05:17,880 --> 01:05:20,549
-Is he really that good?
-You can see for yourself.

1728
01:05:21,284 --> 01:05:23,452
CATCH!
ONION

1729
01:05:23,786 --> 01:05:25,521
1. GRILL ONION

1730
01:05:26,722 --> 01:05:27,723
CARROT

1731
01:05:27,790 --> 01:05:28,791
CABBAGE

1732
01:05:28,858 --> 01:05:29,859
GREEN ONION

1733
01:05:30,159 --> 01:05:31,394
GARLIC

1734
01:05:32,128 --> 01:05:34,096
SHIITAKE, KING OYSTER MUSHROOM

1735
01:05:34,163 --> 01:05:37,366
Chef Jong-won made
sloppy cuts of vegetables

1736
01:05:37,433 --> 01:05:40,403
to get vegetable broth from them.

1737
01:05:41,070 --> 01:05:43,906
-"Sloppy cuts"?
-I'm sorry. What I meant was…

1738
01:05:43,973 --> 01:05:45,041
Detailed cuts.

1739
01:05:45,107 --> 01:05:46,442
Wait, when?

1740
01:05:46,509 --> 01:05:48,945
How did he do that in a minute?

1741
01:05:49,011 --> 01:05:50,746
To get the veggie broth quickly,

1742
01:05:50,813 --> 01:05:52,114
I need maximum surface area.

1743
01:05:52,181 --> 01:05:53,582
It was intentional.

1744
01:05:53,649 --> 01:05:55,117
-Into thin pieces.
-And wide.

1745
01:05:55,184 --> 01:05:57,720
Then it'll give off broth quickly.

1746
01:05:58,220 --> 01:06:01,791
He grilled half an onion
and put that on top.

1747
01:06:01,857 --> 01:06:04,493
That'll make the broth sweeter
and add a nice flavor.

1748
01:06:04,760 --> 01:06:05,761
I SEE

1749
01:06:05,828 --> 01:06:08,664
Yes, I heard grilled veggies
make sweeter broth.

1750
01:06:08,731 --> 01:06:12,501
If you want to make veggie broth,
you can make note of that.

1751
01:06:12,568 --> 01:06:14,937
He's using a Chinese kitchen knife
with his left hand,

1752
01:06:15,004 --> 01:06:16,439
but doesn't he look clumsy?

1753
01:06:16,505 --> 01:06:19,275
-He's still clumsy. He can't even cut it.
-It's not… Is it too dull?

1754
01:06:19,342 --> 01:06:21,510
-His knife skills never improve.
-It doesn't.

1755
01:06:21,577 --> 01:06:22,912
What's that meat?

1756
01:06:22,979 --> 01:06:24,447
-Beef brisket.
-Beef brisket.

1757
01:06:24,513 --> 01:06:27,350
He mixed it with egg white and tuna sauce.

1758
01:06:27,416 --> 01:06:29,418
-Tuna sauce.
-Tuna sauce.

1759
01:06:29,485 --> 01:06:31,053
-You added tuna sauce?
-Yes.

1760
01:06:31,120 --> 01:06:32,521
Why tuna sauce?

1761
01:06:32,588 --> 01:06:35,091
-To season it.
-To season it.

1762
01:06:35,424 --> 01:06:37,259
NEXT, THE MEAT SAUCE

1763
01:06:37,560 --> 01:06:40,129
THE KEY IS PEANUT BUTTER!

1764
01:06:40,196 --> 01:06:41,497
Are you mixing tuna sauce

1765
01:06:41,564 --> 01:06:43,199
-with peanut butter?
-Tuna sauce?

1766
01:06:43,265 --> 01:06:45,835
-He's using lots of tuna sauce.
-What are you making, Poong?

1767
01:06:45,901 --> 01:06:47,336
The sauce.

1768
01:06:47,403 --> 01:06:49,739
-Sugar.
-The sauce?

1769
01:06:49,805 --> 01:06:50,940
GLANCES

1770
01:06:51,007 --> 01:06:53,609
Chef Jong-won glanced at him

1771
01:06:53,676 --> 01:06:55,778
-like he's absurd.
-Potato.

1772
01:06:55,845 --> 01:06:58,614
JONG-WON SEEMS RELAXED SO FAR

1773
01:06:59,115 --> 01:07:00,750
POONG'S CHILI OIL IS DONE!

1774
01:07:00,816 --> 01:07:02,451
-Chili oil.
-He always makes chili oil.

1775
01:07:02,518 --> 01:07:04,320
-He uses chili oil.
-It always looks nice.

1776
01:07:04,387 --> 01:07:07,056
He always makes chili oil,

1777
01:07:07,123 --> 01:07:08,524
and he makes good use of it.

1778
01:07:08,591 --> 01:07:10,526
-Let's give it to him.
-It goes in the sauce.

1779
01:07:10,593 --> 01:07:12,495
It smells really good.

1780
01:07:12,561 --> 01:07:14,964
He tastes it every now and then.

1781
01:07:15,031 --> 01:07:17,500
-He's never done that.
-There he goes again.

1782
01:07:17,566 --> 01:07:18,934
He's tasting it today.

1783
01:07:19,001 --> 01:07:21,937
His hands are shaking
more than usual today.

1784
01:07:22,004 --> 01:07:23,873
He feigned indifference,
but he must be nervous.

1785
01:07:23,939 --> 01:07:26,175
-Why are you so serious?
-Yes, he's odd.

1786
01:07:26,242 --> 01:07:28,010
-If he wins, it's a big win.
-It is.

1787
01:07:28,077 --> 01:07:31,280
Poong begins to show his ambition.

1788
01:07:31,347 --> 01:07:32,848
He's showing his true colors.

1789
01:07:32,915 --> 01:07:34,216
Huh?

1790
01:07:34,283 --> 01:07:35,785
The heat is really high.

1791
01:07:35,851 --> 01:07:38,354
He's roasting cabbage.

1792
01:07:38,421 --> 01:07:40,022
-Over very high heat.
-Over high heat.

1793
01:07:40,089 --> 01:07:42,291
Why are you roasting it over high heat?

1794
01:07:42,358 --> 01:07:45,861
To cause the Maillard reaction
and make it sweeter.

1795
01:07:45,928 --> 01:07:47,530
So that makes it sweeter.

1796
01:07:48,597 --> 01:07:49,932
Ten minutes!

1797
01:07:49,999 --> 01:07:51,133
-It's been five minutes.
-Time flies.

1798
01:07:51,200 --> 01:07:52,435
Is that water?

1799
01:07:52,501 --> 01:07:55,471
-He's parboiling it in water.
-Why did you throw the meat in water?

1800
01:07:55,538 --> 01:07:58,674
I coated it with starch
and dipped it briefly in water

1801
01:07:58,741 --> 01:08:00,776
just before it boils to make it tender.

1802
01:08:01,077 --> 01:08:03,145
LOW HEAT

1803
01:08:03,212 --> 01:08:04,880
I didn't know that was a thing.

1804
01:08:04,947 --> 01:08:07,116
The cabbage is quite burnt.

1805
01:08:07,183 --> 01:08:08,918
-It looks good.
-It looks good.

1806
01:08:08,984 --> 01:08:12,021
It brings out the flavor
almost four times as much.

1807
01:08:12,088 --> 01:08:13,722
Next, butter.

1808
01:08:13,789 --> 01:08:15,024
It smells so sweet and nice.

1809
01:08:15,091 --> 01:08:16,792
Just that cabbage itself looks good.

1810
01:08:16,859 --> 01:08:19,195
He's seasoning the cabbage.

1811
01:08:19,929 --> 01:08:23,199
I usually add that sauce on raw cabbage.

1812
01:08:23,265 --> 01:08:25,568
I didn't know you could put it
on roasted cabbage.

1813
01:08:25,634 --> 01:08:29,004
-Kyuhyun has some experience in cooking.
-He does.

1814
01:08:29,805 --> 01:08:30,906
-Cucumber.
-Cucumber.

1815
01:08:30,973 --> 01:08:34,009
Chef Jong-won grabbed a cucumber first.

1816
01:08:34,076 --> 01:08:37,012
-Poong said he'd also use cucumbers.
-He got it too.

1817
01:08:37,079 --> 01:08:39,615
Yes, he just grabbed one.

1818
01:08:39,682 --> 01:08:41,083
What are you doing?

1819
01:08:41,150 --> 01:08:42,551
-What is it?
-He's acting up.

1820
01:08:42,618 --> 01:08:44,620
-He got the steps mixed up.
-I guess so.

1821
01:08:44,687 --> 01:08:48,524
Is he removing the seeds?

1822
01:08:48,591 --> 01:08:50,526
-Remove the seeds.
-Remove the seeds.

1823
01:08:50,593 --> 01:08:51,927
We do that in Western cuisine.

1824
01:08:51,994 --> 01:08:53,929
You remove the cucumber seeds
in Western cuisine?

1825
01:08:53,996 --> 01:08:56,165
Let's see if Poong does that.

1826
01:08:56,232 --> 01:08:57,867
-I doubt it.
-Not in Chinese cuisine.

1827
01:08:57,933 --> 01:08:59,635
Is it true that the rough surface

1828
01:08:59,702 --> 01:09:02,371
-on the cucumber skin is the bitter part?
-That's…

1829
01:09:02,438 --> 01:09:05,007
Poong preps the cucumber!

1830
01:09:05,074 --> 01:09:06,375
Watch your hand.

1831
01:09:06,442 --> 01:09:09,278
He peels off some of the rough skin.

1832
01:09:09,345 --> 01:09:11,580
I think he'll make
long slices with the peeler.

1833
01:09:11,647 --> 01:09:13,849
He's trying to make long slices.

1834
01:09:13,916 --> 01:09:15,551
-He said he'd roll it.
-Did he toss the skin?

1835
01:09:15,618 --> 01:09:18,654
-Put it down first before you use that.
-That's it.

1836
01:09:19,054 --> 01:09:20,055
DOESN'T PEEL

1837
01:09:20,122 --> 01:09:22,224
Is it better to put it down?

1838
01:09:22,291 --> 01:09:23,759
-Why won't it work?
-It won't work.

1839
01:09:23,826 --> 01:09:26,295
Flip it. Use the other side.

1840
01:09:28,330 --> 01:09:29,331
Damn it!

1841
01:09:29,798 --> 01:09:31,534
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

1842
01:09:33,602 --> 01:09:34,603
SURPRISED

1843
01:09:34,670 --> 01:09:36,772
-He broke the peeler!
-Damn it!

1844
01:09:37,506 --> 01:09:38,507
ANOTHER PEELER

1845
01:09:39,775 --> 01:09:41,043
The power of black raspberries.

1846
01:09:41,110 --> 01:09:42,978
-Okay. Watch your hand.
-Into thin pieces.

1847
01:09:43,045 --> 01:09:44,046
Watch out.

1848
01:09:45,281 --> 01:09:47,716
-He'll probably use that to make shapes.
-Wide slices.

1849
01:09:47,783 --> 01:09:52,421
There's a Chinese dish called
Sichuan garlic pork slices,

1850
01:09:52,488 --> 01:09:54,156
and you wrap cucumber slices with meat.

1851
01:09:54,456 --> 01:09:55,457
IT'S AN ACTUAL THING?

1852
01:09:55,524 --> 01:09:58,527
-And he's doing that?
-Why am I excited about Poong's dish?

1853
01:09:59,128 --> 01:10:00,829
I'M EXCITED TOO

1854
01:10:00,896 --> 01:10:02,565
At this point in time,

1855
01:10:02,631 --> 01:10:06,168
-Kyuhyun is more intrigued by Poong.
-He's excited about it.

1856
01:10:06,235 --> 01:10:08,137
-I'm curious.
-You are?

1857
01:10:08,204 --> 01:10:10,306
It feels like the guy who lives next door
whipping something up.

1858
01:10:10,372 --> 01:10:11,507
It looks good.

1859
01:10:11,574 --> 01:10:13,642
He mixes the brisket with the sauce.

1860
01:10:15,511 --> 01:10:17,846
JONG-WON FINISHES PREPPING THE CUCUMBER

1861
01:10:17,913 --> 01:10:20,349
4. MIX CUCUMBER PIECES WITH SESAME OIL,
SEAWEED FLAKES, MINCED GARLIC

1862
01:10:21,483 --> 01:10:24,587
SON'S 6 VEGGIE SNACKS
2. SEASONED CUCUMBER WITH SEAWEED

1863
01:10:24,653 --> 01:10:25,654
YUM

1864
01:10:26,322 --> 01:10:27,323
WHAT'S THE THIRD VEGGIE?

1865
01:10:27,389 --> 01:10:28,490
CARROT

1866
01:10:28,557 --> 01:10:29,558
Carrot.

1867
01:10:30,292 --> 01:10:31,527
Olive oil.

1868
01:10:32,461 --> 01:10:34,029
LEMON JUICE, WHOLE GRAIN MUSTARD

1869
01:10:34,096 --> 01:10:35,097
Like <i>râpées</i>.

1870
01:10:35,164 --> 01:10:37,433
The best ingredients that go with carrots…

1871
01:10:37,499 --> 01:10:39,602
-Yes?
-…are citrus fruits.

1872
01:10:39,668 --> 01:10:42,471
Tangerines. Is he using an orange?
I thought it was a tangerine.

1873
01:10:42,538 --> 01:10:45,074
He's adding orange zest.

1874
01:10:45,140 --> 01:10:46,141
It sounds good.

1875
01:10:46,208 --> 01:10:49,178
He'll probably use the juice too.

1876
01:10:49,245 --> 01:10:50,246
He adds the orange.

1877
01:10:50,813 --> 01:10:53,449
SON'S 6 VEGGIE SNACKS
3. CARROT AND ORANGE RÂPÉES

1878
01:10:54,984 --> 01:10:56,352
-What's he doing?
-Foil?

1879
01:10:56,418 --> 01:10:57,653
To make a shape?

1880
01:10:58,420 --> 01:10:59,421
TORCH

1881
01:10:59,488 --> 01:11:01,090
-To smoke it.
-Smoking.

1882
01:11:01,390 --> 01:11:02,725
HOW WILL HE MAKE THE SMOKE?

1883
01:11:03,225 --> 01:11:05,661
-Chopsticks?
-Wooden chopsticks.

1884
01:11:05,728 --> 01:11:07,029
You did that before, right?

1885
01:11:07,830 --> 01:11:09,598
It's the torch relay.

1886
01:11:09,865 --> 01:11:13,402
HE BURNED CHOPSTICKS TO BROIL CABBAGE!

1887
01:11:13,936 --> 01:11:16,972
THAT TECHNIQUE IS NOW MINE

1888
01:11:17,673 --> 01:11:19,241
POONG GOBBLES UP NAM-NO

1889
01:11:19,308 --> 01:11:20,309
He's smoking it.

1890
01:11:20,376 --> 01:11:21,510
It won't work.

1891
01:11:21,577 --> 01:11:23,045
-It'll work.
-It will?

1892
01:11:23,112 --> 01:11:24,346
If he puts the lid on, yes.

1893
01:11:24,880 --> 01:11:25,948
6. SMOKE PARBOILED BRISKET

1894
01:11:26,015 --> 01:11:28,784
You should block off the hole.

1895
01:11:29,118 --> 01:11:30,586
WHAT'S JONG-WON'S FOURTH VEGGIE?

1896
01:11:30,653 --> 01:11:33,188
NAPA CABBAGE, DETAILED CUTS

1897
01:11:33,689 --> 01:11:37,059
Chef Jong-won is spreading
barley <i>doenjang</i> between the leaves.

1898
01:11:37,126 --> 01:11:38,727
Like making kimchi. That looks good.

1899
01:11:38,794 --> 01:11:41,730
-Between cabbage leaves.
-We usually dip it in the sauce.

1900
01:11:41,797 --> 01:11:44,300
-It looks good.
-That will make him crave whiskey.

1901
01:11:44,667 --> 01:11:45,934
POONG IS STILL SLICING CUCUMBER

1902
01:11:46,001 --> 01:11:48,070
Poong is still slicing the cucumber.

1903
01:11:48,137 --> 01:11:50,439
What will he do with the cucumber?

1904
01:11:50,506 --> 01:11:51,807
-Five minutes!
-Okay.

1905
01:11:51,874 --> 01:11:53,942
-Already?
-Jung-hwan, you're up.

1906
01:11:54,009 --> 01:11:55,311
Whiskey snacks.

1907
01:11:55,377 --> 01:11:57,146
FIFTH VEGGIE, ROMAINE

1908
01:11:57,212 --> 01:11:59,682
-And romaine?
-He's using just the core.

1909
01:11:59,748 --> 01:12:00,949
Yes, that's the good part.

1910
01:12:01,250 --> 01:12:02,785
7. SPRINKLE SESAME DRESSING
AND SESAME ON ROMAINE

1911
01:12:02,851 --> 01:12:05,287
That dressing makes anything delicious.

1912
01:12:05,821 --> 01:12:08,390
SON'S 6 VEGGIE SNACKS
5. SESAME ROMAINE

1913
01:12:08,457 --> 01:12:09,658
And he's smoking meat here.

1914
01:12:09,725 --> 01:12:12,227
This is it. He'll open it later.

1915
01:12:12,294 --> 01:12:14,263
-I don't smell anything yet.
-Nothing yet.

1916
01:12:14,596 --> 01:12:16,298
THE LEFTOVER CHILI PEANUT BUTTER SAUCE

1917
01:12:16,365 --> 01:12:18,167
What are you making, Poong?

1918
01:12:18,233 --> 01:12:19,735
-Sauce.
-What sauce?

1919
01:12:19,802 --> 01:12:21,737
The sauce for cucumber.

1920
01:12:21,804 --> 01:12:22,938
The sauce for cucumber.

1921
01:12:23,005 --> 01:12:26,241
So you'll mix those cucumber slices
with this sauce?

1922
01:12:26,308 --> 01:12:28,310
-Four minutes left.
-He's seasoning the cucumber.

1923
01:12:28,377 --> 01:12:31,847
I see.
He seasons the wide cucumber slices.

1924
01:12:32,247 --> 01:12:34,450
WHAT'S THE LAST ITEM
FOR THE 6 VEGGIE SNACKS?

1925
01:12:34,516 --> 01:12:36,385
He's using a pear.

1926
01:12:36,452 --> 01:12:38,087
Look at how detailed Jong-won is.

1927
01:12:38,153 --> 01:12:40,556
-These are all finger food.
-You're right.

1928
01:12:40,622 --> 01:12:43,559
Goodness. Women would love this.

1929
01:12:43,625 --> 01:12:45,227
Kyuhyun, are you dating anyone?

1930
01:12:45,928 --> 01:12:48,030
Looking… I'm looking for one.

1931
01:12:48,097 --> 01:12:50,399
Once you start dating,
she would love it if you made these.

1932
01:12:50,466 --> 01:12:52,368
-Yes.
-Yes.

1933
01:12:52,935 --> 01:12:54,803
I'll share the recipe if you pick me.

1934
01:12:54,870 --> 01:12:57,072
Then you can make it for your girlfriend.

1935
01:12:57,139 --> 01:12:58,707
He's making his case.

1936
01:12:58,774 --> 01:13:00,776
-He never goes that far.
-He doesn't.

1937
01:13:01,443 --> 01:13:04,046
If you eat this with her,
you can marry her.

1938
01:13:04,113 --> 01:13:05,214
The moment she eats this,

1939
01:13:05,280 --> 01:13:08,250
she'll pretty much
consider this a proposal.

1940
01:13:08,317 --> 01:13:09,685
-Really?
-Yes.

1941
01:13:10,219 --> 01:13:12,821
Poong is now making a dish
good enough to make someone get married.

1942
01:13:12,888 --> 01:13:14,857
-Yes.
-Tomatoes.

1943
01:13:14,923 --> 01:13:17,025
-Are you mixing it with cucumber?
-Yes.

1944
01:13:17,092 --> 01:13:19,695
-Watch your hand.
-Be careful with your hand.

1945
01:13:19,762 --> 01:13:23,298
8. MIX TOMATO AND CUCUMBER WITH THE SAUCE

1946
01:13:24,133 --> 01:13:26,301
If you eat this with her,
you can marry her.

1947
01:13:26,769 --> 01:13:28,937
MAYONNAISE, BASIL PESTO, ANCHOVY SAUCE

1948
01:13:29,004 --> 01:13:31,607
Chef Jong-won is using
cheese, basil pesto, and mayonnaise.

1949
01:13:31,673 --> 01:13:34,543
He's blending everything to make a dip.

1950
01:13:34,610 --> 01:13:35,878
What did you just add?

1951
01:13:35,944 --> 01:13:39,081
Olive oil.
This dressing is called Green Goddess,

1952
01:13:39,148 --> 01:13:40,916
which usually uses anchovy.

1953
01:13:40,983 --> 01:13:43,585
-He used anchovy sauce instead.
-Jung-hwan!

1954
01:13:43,652 --> 01:13:46,121
Can you try the veggie broth right now?

1955
01:13:46,188 --> 01:13:49,224
Does it need to simmer longer?

1956
01:13:49,291 --> 01:13:51,627
-He grilled the onion to make this.
-Or is it ready?

1957
01:13:52,194 --> 01:13:55,197
You don't have much time.
You have about two minutes left.

1958
01:13:55,264 --> 01:13:56,498
YUM

1959
01:13:56,565 --> 01:13:58,434
Does it have a deep flavor?

1960
01:13:59,101 --> 01:14:00,202
SAVORING

1961
01:14:01,437 --> 01:14:03,238
-It tastes sweet.
-Sweet?

1962
01:14:03,305 --> 01:14:05,474
It tastes unbelievably rich.

1963
01:14:06,108 --> 01:14:07,276
I knew it.

1964
01:14:07,342 --> 01:14:09,678
THE BROTH TASTES SWEET AND RICH

1965
01:14:09,745 --> 01:14:11,914
-I knew it.
-It's sweet and nice.

1966
01:14:11,980 --> 01:14:14,016
SERVED IN A TEAPOT

1967
01:14:14,082 --> 01:14:15,984
-The cucumber.
-Serve the cucumber.

1968
01:14:17,085 --> 01:14:20,289
-He's going to fill it up.
-I see.

1969
01:14:20,355 --> 01:14:23,258
He's trying to make a dome shape.

1970
01:14:23,325 --> 01:14:25,360
What's Poong doing?

1971
01:14:25,427 --> 01:14:26,929
I'm going to plate it.

1972
01:14:26,995 --> 01:14:29,498
WHAT'S POONG TRYING TO COPY?

1973
01:14:29,865 --> 01:14:32,668
THE MARBLE MADE WITH AVOCADO SLICES!

1974
01:14:32,968 --> 01:14:36,638
THAT TECHNIQUE IS NOW MINE

1975
01:14:36,939 --> 01:14:39,274
WHEN THE GOOD VIBES PRESENTATION
MEETS POONG…

1976
01:14:39,741 --> 01:14:42,377
He'll set those in the bowl,
fill it up with meat,

1977
01:14:42,444 --> 01:14:44,813
turn it over, and make a dome.

1978
01:14:44,880 --> 01:14:46,815
Do you think so? It looks odd.

1979
01:14:46,882 --> 01:14:48,450
I'm looking forward to it.

1980
01:14:48,517 --> 01:14:49,818
BURRATA

1981
01:14:49,885 --> 01:14:50,886
All done.

1982
01:14:50,953 --> 01:14:52,321
What's that?

1983
01:14:52,387 --> 01:14:54,623
-Cheese. Burrata.
-Cheese?

1984
01:14:54,690 --> 01:14:56,124
-Burrata.
-Burrata.

1985
01:14:56,191 --> 01:14:57,626
Is it smoked?

1986
01:14:57,693 --> 01:14:58,694
SNIFF

1987
01:14:58,760 --> 01:15:01,497
-It happened. I'm sure it did.
-Try and see if it's smoked.

1988
01:15:01,563 --> 01:15:04,132
What do you think?
Does the meat smell smoked?

1989
01:15:05,734 --> 01:15:07,503
It smells like <i>jwibullori</i>.

1990
01:15:07,569 --> 01:15:11,039
-Can you try a small bite?
-Did he say <i>jwibullori</i>?

1991
01:15:11,106 --> 01:15:13,308
-The meat?
-The meat.

1992
01:15:13,375 --> 01:15:15,310
-I should try the meat.
-Exactly.

1993
01:15:15,377 --> 01:15:17,779
-Is it smoked?
-See if it has a smoky flavor.

1994
01:15:17,846 --> 01:15:19,615
You have a minute left!

1995
01:15:19,681 --> 01:15:21,149
CHECKING THE SMOKED BRISKET

1996
01:15:21,216 --> 01:15:24,253
Does the meat have a smoky flavor?

1997
01:15:24,319 --> 01:15:26,688
What's wrong? No?

1998
01:15:27,422 --> 01:15:28,423
What is it?

1999
01:15:28,490 --> 01:15:30,225
-Is it an emergency?
-Is it?

2000
01:15:30,292 --> 01:15:32,461
-Turn that on.
-It's an emergency.

2001
01:15:32,528 --> 01:15:34,429
I was hoping for a strong scent,

2002
01:15:34,496 --> 01:15:36,532
-but it isn't strong.
-I don't have enough time for that.

2003
01:15:36,598 --> 01:15:39,268
-It's there, but it's rather subtle.
-I see.

2004
01:15:39,968 --> 01:15:42,604
WE'RE EXPECTING A MARBLE LIKE THIS ONE

2005
01:15:43,906 --> 01:15:45,207
WHAT WILL IT LOOK LIKE?

2006
01:15:45,274 --> 01:15:46,775
I NEED TO SEE A CUCUMBER MARBLE!

2007
01:15:46,842 --> 01:15:48,577
Slowly. Be careful.

2008
01:15:48,644 --> 01:15:51,046
-That's good.
-Yes.

2009
01:15:51,113 --> 01:15:52,714
Things are going well for him.

2010
01:15:52,781 --> 01:15:54,349
One minute to go!

2011
01:15:54,416 --> 01:15:56,552
One minute! Please hurry!

2012
01:15:56,618 --> 01:15:57,986
One minute!

2013
01:15:58,854 --> 01:16:00,422
RIP OUT A SINGLE CABBAGE LEAF

2014
01:16:00,689 --> 01:16:03,091
AND ADD OTHER VEGGIES

2015
01:16:03,158 --> 01:16:05,694
KING OYSTER MUSHROOM, CARROT, SHIITAKE

2016
01:16:05,761 --> 01:16:07,329
-Nam-no.
-Yes?

2017
01:16:07,396 --> 01:16:09,398
This is UNICHEF. Can you just tie that?

2018
01:16:09,464 --> 01:16:10,899
10. TIE VEGGIES INTO A BOUQUET

2019
01:16:10,966 --> 01:16:12,134
Thirty-five seconds!

2020
01:16:12,200 --> 01:16:13,602
I'm in trouble.

2021
01:16:13,669 --> 01:16:16,405
-I have to make smoke…
-You need to wrap up.

2022
01:16:16,471 --> 01:16:19,441
-What is it?
-Poong continues to grumble.

2023
01:16:19,508 --> 01:16:20,642
One more time?

2024
01:16:21,209 --> 01:16:23,045
READY TO SMOKE THE DISH ONE LAST TIME!

2025
01:16:23,111 --> 01:16:25,180
Jong-won begins to plate the dish.

2026
01:16:26,081 --> 01:16:29,051
-Twenty seconds!
-You're short on time, Jong-won.

2027
01:16:29,117 --> 01:16:30,852
-Twenty seconds!
-Get the dishes ready.

2028
01:16:30,919 --> 01:16:32,955
Veggies are Perfect for Whis-Kyu.

2029
01:16:33,021 --> 01:16:34,957
-One more time.
-Ten seconds. Nine.

2030
01:16:35,023 --> 01:16:37,359
-Eight. Seven.
-Eight. Seven.

2031
01:16:37,426 --> 01:16:40,228
THIS IS HIS SILENT OUTCRY

2032
01:16:40,295 --> 01:16:41,363
-Ten seconds.
-I should've tasted it.

2033
01:16:41,430 --> 01:16:43,065
THE BOUQUET NAM-NO TIED

2034
01:16:43,498 --> 01:16:47,102
CALMLY PUTS IT IN A BOWL

2035
01:16:48,036 --> 01:16:50,906
FINISHING THE DISH WITH THE DRESSING

2036
01:16:50,973 --> 01:16:52,708
WHAT ABOUT POONG?

2037
01:16:53,442 --> 01:16:55,510
-Time's up.
-Time's up.

2038
01:16:55,577 --> 01:16:56,578
Please ring the bell.

2039
01:16:57,145 --> 01:16:59,047
Who's first? Poong ended first.

2040
01:16:59,114 --> 01:17:00,616
That was clever.

2041
01:17:00,682 --> 01:17:01,683
BLOWING

2042
01:17:02,784 --> 01:17:05,320
-Jong-won finishes too.
-He's done.

2043
01:17:05,387 --> 01:17:08,690
This looks just like a dish
I had in Hong Kong two days ago.

2044
01:17:09,124 --> 01:17:11,059
THE SON-POONG BATTLE IS OVER!

2045
01:17:11,126 --> 01:17:13,161
Great work.

2046
01:17:13,228 --> 01:17:14,997
THE WHISKEY SNACKS ARE SERVED

2047
01:17:15,530 --> 01:17:17,132
They both look good.

2048
01:17:17,766 --> 01:17:20,702
Nice job with the presentation, Poong.

2049
01:17:20,769 --> 01:17:22,704
And now, both whiskey snacks

2050
01:17:22,771 --> 01:17:26,074
were finished just for Kyuhyun.

2051
01:17:26,141 --> 01:17:27,242
Gosh.

2052
01:17:27,309 --> 01:17:29,544
Chef Jong-won's dish

2053
01:17:29,611 --> 01:17:33,382
looks elaborately and exquisitely made.

2054
01:17:33,448 --> 01:17:36,218
But Webtoon Artist Poong's dish

2055
01:17:36,284 --> 01:17:40,122
had me keep wondering what it'd be like.

2056
01:17:40,188 --> 01:17:42,224
-Like, "Will it be okay?"
-I was a bit worried.

2057
01:17:42,290 --> 01:17:45,761
But it feels like a close friend of mine
whipped it up for me, so I'm excited.

2058
01:17:45,827 --> 01:17:49,431
We don't know
if the dish has a smoky flavor.

2059
01:17:49,498 --> 01:17:51,667
Please try Chinese-ish Poong!

2060
01:17:52,167 --> 01:17:54,736
COLD CUCUMBER SALAD
HIDDEN UNDER A VEIL OF SMOKE

2061
01:17:55,437 --> 01:17:58,473
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
CHINESE-ISH POONG!

2062
01:17:59,307 --> 01:18:01,343
OPENING THE LID

2063
01:18:02,844 --> 01:18:05,280
DOES IT CONTAIN A SMOKY FLAVOR?

2064
01:18:05,347 --> 01:18:06,615
-That's nice.
-Hey.

2065
01:18:06,682 --> 01:18:09,051
-It smells good.
-It smells smoky.

2066
01:18:09,284 --> 01:18:10,585
SO PROUD

2067
01:18:10,652 --> 01:18:13,522
-He says it smells smoky.
-I love the presentation.

2068
01:18:13,588 --> 01:18:14,823
It looks great.

2069
01:18:14,890 --> 01:18:17,626
It has me wondering
what's beneath the cucumber,

2070
01:18:17,693 --> 01:18:18,894
making me curious.

2071
01:18:18,960 --> 01:18:20,529
THE DISH MAKES HIM CURIOUS

2072
01:18:20,595 --> 01:18:22,431
-I see.
-How should I attack this?

2073
01:18:22,497 --> 01:18:25,033
Eat lots of cucumber
with meat and veggies.

2074
01:18:25,100 --> 01:18:27,703
Have a sip of whiskey, and then the dish.

2075
01:18:27,769 --> 01:18:29,838
-Whiskey, server.
-I got it ready.

2076
01:18:29,905 --> 01:18:31,440
SERVER AHN IS PREPARED

2077
01:18:32,007 --> 01:18:33,141
-Welcome, sir.
-Yes.

2078
01:18:33,208 --> 01:18:34,643
"Welcome, sir"?

2079
01:18:34,710 --> 01:18:35,711
-Your usual.
-His usual.

2080
01:18:35,777 --> 01:18:37,312
-A glass of loneliness.
-Yes.

2081
01:18:37,979 --> 01:18:39,881
FILLING UP THE GLASS
WITH LONELINESS

2082
01:18:39,948 --> 01:18:42,184
Enjoy your drink of happiness.

2083
01:18:42,250 --> 01:18:44,486
ENJOY HAPPINESS TODAY
INSTEAD OF LONELINESS

2084
01:18:45,253 --> 01:18:47,456
He's the type who mixes a bit of water.

2085
01:18:47,522 --> 01:18:49,424
To bring out the aroma.

2086
01:18:49,491 --> 01:18:51,059
SPINNING

2087
01:18:52,227 --> 01:18:54,262
-He smells the drink.
-He spins it

2088
01:18:54,329 --> 01:18:56,932
like a lonely hunter.

2089
01:18:56,998 --> 01:18:58,033
A glass of loneliness.

2090
01:18:58,100 --> 01:19:00,802
When I return home at midnight after work,

2091
01:19:00,869 --> 01:19:02,971
I enjoy a glass of whiskey like this.

2092
01:19:03,038 --> 01:19:04,639
As you wrap up your day.

2093
01:19:04,706 --> 01:19:05,841
HESITATES

2094
01:19:05,907 --> 01:19:08,043
Let me cut it first
to have a bite right away.

2095
01:19:08,110 --> 01:19:09,678
CURIOUS

2096
01:19:09,745 --> 01:19:11,046
-May I undo this?
-Can he?

2097
01:19:11,113 --> 01:19:12,848
Yes, whatever is easier for you.

2098
01:19:13,548 --> 01:19:15,450
It's filled with lots of stuff.

2099
01:19:15,517 --> 01:19:17,385
-You smoked the meat too.
-I did.

2100
01:19:17,452 --> 01:19:20,689
-It's actually quite strong.
-Is it?

2101
01:19:20,756 --> 01:19:23,058
-I can smell it all the way from here.
-I can too.

2102
01:19:23,125 --> 01:19:25,560
-So the cucumber and meat at once?
-Yes, lots of cucumber slices.

2103
01:19:25,627 --> 01:19:27,729
-Grab lots of slices.
-Yes.

2104
01:19:27,796 --> 01:19:29,631
Will it go well with whiskey?

2105
01:19:30,298 --> 01:19:31,867
He looks so cool.

2106
01:19:31,933 --> 01:19:33,502
It's like a scene from a whiskey ad.

2107
01:19:34,536 --> 01:19:35,971
-He savors the drink.
-Yes.

2108
01:19:36,037 --> 01:19:38,607
-It's like watching an ad.
-After a long day.

2109
01:19:38,673 --> 01:19:40,942
SIGH

2110
01:19:41,443 --> 01:19:43,612
A BITE OF SNACK BEFORE THE DRINK WEARS OFF

2111
01:19:44,780 --> 01:19:45,781
CRUNCH

2112
01:19:46,815 --> 01:19:48,483
SMILING

2113
01:19:48,550 --> 01:19:51,820
He was a bit scared and worried.

2114
01:19:52,854 --> 01:19:53,855
GLARE

2115
01:19:53,922 --> 01:19:55,791
-He's looking at him.
-He looked.

2116
01:19:55,857 --> 01:19:59,561
-Glaring equals good.
-Yes, if he glares, it means it's good.

2117
01:20:01,997 --> 01:20:03,265
I want to have him as my master.

2118
01:20:04,933 --> 01:20:06,268
I want to have him as my master.

2119
01:20:06,334 --> 01:20:07,702
EXHILARATING

2120
01:20:08,036 --> 01:20:09,104
POONG'S BAR SNACKS NEVER GO WRONG

2121
01:20:09,171 --> 01:20:10,505
Wait.

2122
01:20:10,572 --> 01:20:12,474
It's an emergency for Jong-won.

2123
01:20:12,541 --> 01:20:14,442
The meat is extremely tender.

2124
01:20:14,509 --> 01:20:16,311
The moment I had a bite,

2125
01:20:16,378 --> 01:20:18,580
the meat gave off all of its juice

2126
01:20:18,647 --> 01:20:20,849
while the cucumber slices kept crunching.

2127
01:20:20,916 --> 01:20:24,052
Then, the sauce mixes
with everything on the inside.

2128
01:20:24,119 --> 01:20:25,620
It's driving me crazy.

2129
01:20:25,687 --> 01:20:26,688
HIGH PRAISE

2130
01:20:26,755 --> 01:20:28,223
How did you make the sauce?

2131
01:20:28,290 --> 01:20:30,458
I mixed chili oil and peanut butter.

2132
01:20:30,525 --> 01:20:32,894
<i>Then I added vinegar and lemon juice</i>
<i>for sourness.</i>

2133
01:20:32,961 --> 01:20:34,896
<i>For saltiness,</i>
<i>some tuna sauce and soy sauce.</i>

2134
01:20:34,963 --> 01:20:36,431
<i>For sweetness, sugar and cooking wine.</i>

2135
01:20:36,665 --> 01:20:37,699
AMAZED

2136
01:20:37,766 --> 01:20:39,568
The sauce is insane.

2137
01:20:39,634 --> 01:20:42,437
He says the sauce is insane
and wants Poong as his master.

2138
01:20:44,306 --> 01:20:45,674
This is really good.

2139
01:20:45,740 --> 01:20:47,142
Who did you learn this from?

2140
01:20:47,209 --> 01:20:48,910
I watched other chefs

2141
01:20:48,977 --> 01:20:51,213
appear on TV and copied them.

2142
01:20:51,279 --> 01:20:52,881
He's truly a thief.

2143
01:20:52,948 --> 01:20:54,282
THE INCARNATION OF STEALING

2144
01:20:54,349 --> 01:20:55,750
You surprised me.

2145
01:20:55,817 --> 01:20:58,253
STICK AROUND LONG ENOUGH
AND EVEN POONG GETS THE HANG OF IT

2146
01:20:58,320 --> 01:21:00,655
-Does it go well with whiskey?
-So well.

2147
01:21:01,256 --> 01:21:04,392
-There's burrata inside.
-Yes, he used burrata.

2148
01:21:04,459 --> 01:21:07,929
The mix of cheese, cucumber,
and peanut butter is always good.

2149
01:21:07,996 --> 01:21:10,031
There's the cheese.

2150
01:21:10,098 --> 01:21:11,766
Cheese and meat.

2151
01:21:11,833 --> 01:21:15,403
He already loved it
even without the cheese.

2152
01:21:15,470 --> 01:21:17,339
He tries it with the burrata this time.

2153
01:21:17,973 --> 01:21:20,041
CURIOUS

2154
01:21:21,243 --> 01:21:22,244
GLARES AGAIN

2155
01:21:22,310 --> 01:21:23,511
He looks at Poong again.

2156
01:21:23,578 --> 01:21:25,046
"Who is that guy?"

2157
01:21:25,113 --> 01:21:26,848
-"Who is he?"
-He only glared at me once.

2158
01:21:27,148 --> 01:21:28,516
LAUGHING OUT LOUD

2159
01:21:28,583 --> 01:21:29,751
Is it good?

2160
01:21:30,886 --> 01:21:32,821
This is the snack I need for whiskey.

2161
01:21:32,888 --> 01:21:35,857
-I see. You won't even try the next one?
-Before you try the other one?

2162
01:21:35,924 --> 01:21:37,959
When I had it with the burrata,

2163
01:21:38,026 --> 01:21:40,528
it even added that cheesy and rich flavor,

2164
01:21:40,595 --> 01:21:42,230
making it much better.

2165
01:21:43,331 --> 01:21:45,533
I'm glad you tried it with cheese.

2166
01:21:45,600 --> 01:21:47,769
-I'm in shock.
-You are?

2167
01:21:47,836 --> 01:21:48,837
He's in shock.

2168
01:21:48,904 --> 01:21:52,340
Next, Chef Jong-won's dish,
Veggies are Perfect for Whis-Kyu.

2169
01:21:53,375 --> 01:21:55,110
A CUP OF POT-AU-FEU
FOR A TASTE OF VEGETABLES

2170
01:21:55,710 --> 01:21:57,979
6 CRUDITÉS WITH GREEN GODDESS SAUCE,
PERFECT WITH WHISKEY

2171
01:21:58,380 --> 01:22:00,148
DOENJANG NAPA CABBAGE

2172
01:22:00,548 --> 01:22:02,284
CARROT AND ORANGE RÂPÉES

2173
01:22:02,350 --> 01:22:04,185
PEAR

2174
01:22:04,486 --> 01:22:06,588
SESAME ROMAINE

2175
01:22:07,656 --> 01:22:09,157
SEASONED CUCUMBER WITH SEAWEED

2176
01:22:10,325 --> 01:22:12,327
ROASTED CABBAGE

2177
01:22:12,627 --> 01:22:16,398
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
VEGGIES ARE PERFECT FOR WHIS-KYU

2178
01:22:17,499 --> 01:22:19,567
Please enjoy the vegetable aroma
as much as possible.

2179
01:22:19,634 --> 01:22:21,636
He's serving the pot-au-feu.

2180
01:22:21,703 --> 01:22:23,505
The vegetable broth.

2181
01:22:23,571 --> 01:22:24,906
Is there a particular order?

2182
01:22:24,973 --> 01:22:27,776
Please start with the cucumber
to refresh your mouth.

2183
01:22:27,842 --> 01:22:30,445
Then you can enjoy it counterclockwise.

2184
01:22:30,512 --> 01:22:33,248
-Counterclockwise.
-Going counterclockwise.

2185
01:22:33,315 --> 01:22:35,617
He just told me to refresh my mouth,
which must mean

2186
01:22:35,684 --> 01:22:38,720
-I should forget Poong's dish.
-Yes, forget it all.

2187
01:22:38,787 --> 01:22:40,121
-Forget the cucumber.
-Forget it.

2188
01:22:40,188 --> 01:22:42,824
Forget his cucumber with mine.

2189
01:22:42,891 --> 01:22:43,959
The cucumber first.

2190
01:22:44,859 --> 01:22:45,860
Whiskey…

2191
01:22:45,927 --> 01:22:47,529
CRUNCH

2192
01:22:47,929 --> 01:22:48,930
EYEBROWS UP

2193
01:22:48,997 --> 01:22:50,165
So?

2194
01:22:50,832 --> 01:22:51,833
What's this sauce?

2195
01:22:53,268 --> 01:22:54,836
TRIES JUST THE SAUCE

2196
01:22:55,470 --> 01:22:57,472
There must be something about it.

2197
01:22:58,373 --> 01:22:59,507
What is it?

2198
01:22:59,574 --> 01:23:00,875
What's the sauce like?

2199
01:23:00,942 --> 01:23:03,311
I really love basil pesto,

2200
01:23:03,378 --> 01:23:06,648
and it has a strong pesto smell,
which goes well with the veggies.

2201
01:23:08,149 --> 01:23:09,351
Next, the cabbage.

2202
01:23:09,417 --> 01:23:11,286
-That one looks good.
-Roasted cabbage.

2203
01:23:13,588 --> 01:23:14,656
In one bite.

2204
01:23:17,592 --> 01:23:20,028
-What is it?
-It must be sweet and delicious.

2205
01:23:20,095 --> 01:23:21,129
His eyes became huge.

2206
01:23:21,196 --> 01:23:22,364
GLARE

2207
01:23:22,430 --> 01:23:24,332
The cabbage did it.

2208
01:23:24,399 --> 01:23:26,067
That was a long glare.

2209
01:23:26,134 --> 01:23:27,569
The cabbage did it.

2210
01:23:27,635 --> 01:23:29,270
-I can't see. He's blocking him.
-He glares.

2211
01:23:29,337 --> 01:23:30,739
INTERCEPTING THE GLARE

2212
01:23:33,208 --> 01:23:35,977
He'll glare at him at least six times.

2213
01:23:37,278 --> 01:23:38,713
This is cabbage steak.

2214
01:23:38,780 --> 01:23:40,015
-Cabbage steak?
-Really?

2215
01:23:40,081 --> 01:23:41,349
It sounds so good.

2216
01:23:41,416 --> 01:23:44,586
<i>He caused the Maillard reaction</i>
<i>by scorching it, right?</i>

2217
01:23:44,652 --> 01:23:46,287
So it almost tastes like steak.

2218
01:23:46,354 --> 01:23:47,355
GULP

2219
01:23:47,989 --> 01:23:49,624
It felt like he was eating steak.

2220
01:23:50,191 --> 01:23:52,460
He only tried two among seven.

2221
01:23:53,328 --> 01:23:54,929
FIDGETING

2222
01:23:57,165 --> 01:24:00,335
The winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars 2</i>
is grabbing a napkin for him.

2223
01:24:00,402 --> 01:24:01,770
KANG-ROK FOLDS A NAPKIN

2224
01:24:01,836 --> 01:24:03,204
He never did that before.

2225
01:24:03,271 --> 01:24:05,807
-He even returned with great manners.
-He did.

2226
01:24:05,874 --> 01:24:07,842
What are we going to do now?

2227
01:24:07,909 --> 01:24:09,110
Do they teach manners on <i>CCW2</i>?

2228
01:24:09,477 --> 01:24:11,379
KANG-ROK WITH GREAT MANNERS

2229
01:24:11,446 --> 01:24:14,315
Then please try the pot-au-feu
to your left.

2230
01:24:14,382 --> 01:24:16,117
-The veggie broth.
-Just the soup?

2231
01:24:16,184 --> 01:24:17,886
-And drink it?
-It's to drink.

2232
01:24:17,952 --> 01:24:20,522
-What about the veggie bouquet?
-He can take it out.

2233
01:24:20,588 --> 01:24:23,158
-It's like a tea bag.
-That's a tea bag?

2234
01:24:23,224 --> 01:24:25,860
-Michelin-star style.
-Try the soup first.

2235
01:24:25,927 --> 01:24:27,762
You can hold it up and drink it.

2236
01:24:27,829 --> 01:24:28,930
POT-AU-FEU TEA TIME

2237
01:24:32,300 --> 01:24:34,102
-What is it?
-Veggie broth.

2238
01:24:34,169 --> 01:24:35,370
Am I drunk?

2239
01:24:35,437 --> 01:24:36,471
Why?

2240
01:24:36,538 --> 01:24:37,772
Why?

2241
01:24:37,839 --> 01:24:39,841
-Does it taste odd?
-Did you add sugar?

2242
01:24:39,908 --> 01:24:42,243
It's the natural sweetness
from the veggies.

2243
01:24:42,310 --> 01:24:44,479
It tastes like a sweet beverage.

2244
01:24:44,546 --> 01:24:46,314
It must smell so good.

2245
01:24:46,381 --> 01:24:48,116
He grilled the onion before he put it in.

2246
01:24:49,017 --> 01:24:50,919
That makes it taste sweet?

2247
01:24:50,985 --> 01:24:52,387
Veggie broth can be so good.

2248
01:24:52,887 --> 01:24:53,888
The third vegetable.

2249
01:24:53,955 --> 01:24:56,925
-I don't have to dip this, right?
-You can eat it as is.

2250
01:24:56,991 --> 01:24:58,026
Napa cabbage.

2251
01:24:58,093 --> 01:25:00,095
That's the delicious part.

2252
01:25:01,696 --> 01:25:03,198
That has to be good.

2253
01:25:03,264 --> 01:25:05,567
That part of the napa cabbage
is already good on its own.

2254
01:25:06,401 --> 01:25:07,702
Gosh.

2255
01:25:07,769 --> 01:25:11,439
<i>He filled every layer between the leaves</i>
<i>with barley</i> doenjang<i>,</i>

2256
01:25:11,506 --> 01:25:13,475
so it's nice and salty,

2257
01:25:13,541 --> 01:25:15,944
making me crave more whiskey.

2258
01:25:16,010 --> 01:25:19,180
So vegetables are a great snack
for whiskey.

2259
01:25:19,247 --> 01:25:22,283
Why is my mouth watering
while looking at vegetables?

2260
01:25:22,350 --> 01:25:24,619
He makes it look especially good.

2261
01:25:25,153 --> 01:25:26,154
CARROT AND ORANGE RÂPÉES

2262
01:25:26,221 --> 01:25:27,589
Is that carrot?

2263
01:25:28,389 --> 01:25:30,024
YUM

2264
01:25:31,292 --> 01:25:32,293
What is it?

2265
01:25:32,360 --> 01:25:34,229
-It's very sour.
-Sour?

2266
01:25:34,295 --> 01:25:36,431
The carrot is infused with orange.

2267
01:25:36,498 --> 01:25:38,733
THE VEGGIE PLATE
COMES WITH MANY DETAILS PER ITEM

2268
01:25:38,800 --> 01:25:42,170
-He'll need at least seven glasses.
-You're right.

2269
01:25:42,237 --> 01:25:43,838
Next, the pear.

2270
01:25:46,441 --> 01:25:47,575
That's just pear.

2271
01:25:47,642 --> 01:25:50,278
-It's just pear.
-It's a good pear, so I used it as is.

2272
01:25:50,345 --> 01:25:52,547
This is a nice refresher.

2273
01:25:53,848 --> 01:25:55,517
-Let me try the last one.
-Romaine.

2274
01:25:57,018 --> 01:25:59,120
-The finale.
-It's the finale.

2275
01:25:59,187 --> 01:26:01,456
-This is his last drink.
-Yes.

2276
01:26:01,523 --> 01:26:03,124
-He has one snack left.
-He does.

2277
01:26:03,191 --> 01:26:04,592
It's the grand finale.

2278
01:26:06,294 --> 01:26:08,096
GULP

2279
01:26:08,563 --> 01:26:10,331
THE SIXTH, SESAME ROMAINE

2280
01:26:10,398 --> 01:26:11,633
Do I eat the base?

2281
01:26:11,699 --> 01:26:13,301
-No, hold…
-Do I hold this?

2282
01:26:13,368 --> 01:26:14,769
-Yes.
-Okay.

2283
01:26:14,836 --> 01:26:16,571
It's a nice finish.

2284
01:26:19,140 --> 01:26:21,142
Was that a refreshing finale?

2285
01:26:21,209 --> 01:26:22,744
This plate of snacks

2286
01:26:22,810 --> 01:26:25,413
will make me happily tipsy
and help me fall asleep in peace.

2287
01:26:26,581 --> 01:26:27,649
And it's healthy.

2288
01:26:27,715 --> 01:26:29,684
-I don't feel bloated, either.
-Right.

2289
01:26:29,751 --> 01:26:30,818
It was a clean snack.

2290
01:26:31,619 --> 01:26:34,656
-And finishing with warm pot-au-feu.
-The sweet broth.

2291
01:26:34,722 --> 01:26:35,857
SAVORING

2292
01:26:35,924 --> 01:26:37,592
I didn't know
veggie broth can be like that.

2293
01:26:38,226 --> 01:26:39,661
Gosh.

2294
01:26:39,727 --> 01:26:41,829
All right, then.

2295
01:26:42,397 --> 01:26:44,632
BOTH SNACKS WERE PERFECT WITH WHISKEY!

2296
01:26:44,699 --> 01:26:46,601
He'll choose right away.

2297
01:26:46,668 --> 01:26:48,303
-No…
-Kyuhyun is the only one

2298
01:26:48,369 --> 01:26:50,271
who knows what these taste like.

2299
01:26:50,338 --> 01:26:51,806
<i>Press one for Jong-won</i>

2300
01:26:51,873 --> 01:26:53,274
<i>and two for Poong.</i>

2301
01:26:54,042 --> 01:26:55,076
HE CAN'T DECIDE EASILY

2302
01:26:55,143 --> 01:26:56,411
The man who loves whiskey.

2303
01:26:56,477 --> 01:26:58,479
-It's a tough decision.
-It must be.

2304
01:26:58,546 --> 01:27:00,615
-Oh, gosh. I don't know.
-Choose one!

2305
01:27:00,682 --> 01:27:03,117
-You don't know? Did you choose one?
-I don't know.

2306
01:27:03,184 --> 01:27:06,454
-I chose one.
-You did? You were torn.

2307
01:27:06,521 --> 01:27:07,689
Who will it be?

2308
01:27:07,755 --> 01:27:10,391
They're both one of the top contenders,

2309
01:27:10,458 --> 01:27:11,960
and they're good friends.

2310
01:27:12,026 --> 01:27:13,027
So?

2311
01:27:13,094 --> 01:27:15,430
Who did Kyuhyun choose?

2312
01:27:15,496 --> 01:27:17,832
Let's find out the result!

2313
01:27:18,466 --> 01:27:21,035
A perfect snack for whiskey.

2314
01:27:21,102 --> 01:27:24,038
Will Jong-won get his revenge
from last year's loss?

2315
01:27:24,105 --> 01:27:26,941
Or will Poong win against Jong-won

2316
01:27:27,008 --> 01:27:28,810
twice in a row?

2317
01:27:28,876 --> 01:27:31,846
Who did Kyuhyun choose?

2318
01:27:31,913 --> 01:27:35,516
Which whiskey snack did he like better?

2319
01:27:35,583 --> 01:27:37,919
KIM POONG WINS

2320
01:27:37,986 --> 01:27:40,622
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
CHINESE-ISH POONG! WINS

2321
01:27:40,688 --> 01:27:41,856
Kim Poong wins!

2322
01:27:42,590 --> 01:27:44,392
POONG DID IT AGAIN

2323
01:27:44,459 --> 01:27:45,827
Are you serious? This is insane.

2324
01:27:45,893 --> 01:27:46,995
IN GREAT SHOCK

2325
01:27:47,061 --> 01:27:48,930
-Poong wins!
-Great job.

2326
01:27:48,997 --> 01:27:52,200
He now becomes Jong-won's natural enemy!

2327
01:27:52,267 --> 01:27:54,902
I would've enjoyed Chef Jong-won's dish

2328
01:27:54,969 --> 01:27:58,139
at a fine dining restaurant

2329
01:27:58,206 --> 01:28:01,643
with a delighted heart over a drink.

2330
01:28:01,709 --> 01:28:03,177
That would've been delicious.

2331
01:28:03,244 --> 01:28:05,179
But to be honest, Webtoon Artist Poong's…

2332
01:28:05,246 --> 01:28:06,614
Let me be frank.

2333
01:28:06,681 --> 01:28:09,784
-I honestly didn't expect much.
-I see.

2334
01:28:09,851 --> 01:28:12,353
-That's the biggest reason.
-He always does this.

2335
01:28:12,420 --> 01:28:15,423
-That's why.
-The process seems too sloppy.

2336
01:28:15,490 --> 01:28:17,492
So I didn't have a lot of faith in it.

2337
01:28:17,558 --> 01:28:21,963
But the moment I had the first bite
of cucumber, meat, and tomato,

2338
01:28:22,030 --> 01:28:24,132
<i>I was in such shock.</i>

2339
01:28:24,198 --> 01:28:26,934
I don't think I'll ever forget that.

2340
01:28:27,001 --> 01:28:28,236
-That moment.
-It was that good?

2341
01:28:28,303 --> 01:28:33,641
This means Webtoon Artist Poong
has become Jong-won's natural enemy.

2342
01:28:33,708 --> 01:28:36,878
You've won against him twice in a row,
once last year and once this year.

2343
01:28:36,944 --> 01:28:38,680
Today,

2344
01:28:38,746 --> 01:28:41,349
I knew I was up against Chef Jong-won,

2345
01:28:41,416 --> 01:28:44,419
so I paid a little more attention
to the presentation.

2346
01:28:44,485 --> 01:28:47,555
That must've worked positively for me.

2347
01:28:47,622 --> 01:28:49,657
I'd like to dedicate the honor
to Chef Jong-won.

2348
01:28:49,724 --> 01:28:51,426
THE HONOR GOES TO CHEF JONG-WON

2349
01:28:51,492 --> 01:28:52,794
All right.

2350
01:28:53,294 --> 01:28:55,763
-He's one of the top contenders.
-What's going on?

2351
01:28:55,830 --> 01:28:56,864
The best in the world.

2352
01:28:57,365 --> 01:28:59,033
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

2353
01:28:59,100 --> 01:29:01,936
-Hello, we're Girls' Generation.
-Hello, we're Girls' Generation.

2354
01:29:04,238 --> 01:29:07,141
She recently registered her marriage
with Byun Yo-han.

2355
01:29:07,208 --> 01:29:09,310
I thought, "It'd be a miracle
if she even got married."

2356
01:29:09,610 --> 01:29:10,878
MY FRIEND…

2357
01:29:10,945 --> 01:29:12,013
-Today…
-Really?

2358
01:29:12,080 --> 01:29:13,114
FIRST REVEAL ON THE SHOW

2359
01:29:13,181 --> 01:29:15,883
Are you announcing your marriage here?

2360
01:29:15,950 --> 01:29:17,018
My first love…

2361
01:29:17,085 --> 01:29:19,120
-If I get married…
-My dream wedding…

2362
01:29:19,187 --> 01:29:20,455
I want it to be solemn.

2363
01:29:20,521 --> 01:29:21,989
WHO'S GETTING MARRIED?

2364
01:29:22,056 --> 01:29:24,192
Don't you dare get married
without letting me sing.

2365
01:29:24,726 --> 01:29:26,094
-We present her fridge!
-Fridge!

2366
01:29:26,160 --> 01:29:27,729
-Lots of side dishes.
-You're a good cook.

2367
01:29:27,795 --> 01:29:28,896
No way. Did you do it?

2368
01:29:28,963 --> 01:29:30,231
It was my mother-in-law.

2369
01:29:30,298 --> 01:29:31,899
I'm deeply loved by her.

2370
01:29:31,966 --> 01:29:34,769
Let the 15-minute cook-off
for Tiffany begin!

2371
01:29:34,836 --> 01:29:35,903
He gets ready for a party.

2372
01:29:35,970 --> 01:29:37,171
IT'S PARTY TIME HERE

2373
01:29:37,238 --> 01:29:38,239
THIS IS EXCITING

2374
01:29:38,306 --> 01:29:39,607
Is it party time?

2375
01:29:39,674 --> 01:29:40,842
It's a crazy night!

2376
01:29:40,908 --> 01:29:41,876
EXHILARATING

2377
01:29:43,044 --> 01:29:44,612
<i>The winner of this round</i>

2378
01:29:44,679 --> 01:29:46,681
<i>will become the sole first place.</i>

2379
01:29:46,748 --> 01:29:48,015
Are the noodles burnt?

2380
01:29:48,082 --> 01:29:49,117
It's the Maillard reaction.

2381
01:29:49,183 --> 01:29:51,085
-Mint chocolate, in.
-No!

2382
01:29:51,152 --> 01:29:52,286
DID HE CROSS INTO THE DARK SIDE?

2383
01:29:52,353 --> 01:29:53,621
WHY ARE YOU DOING THIS?

2384
01:29:54,021 --> 01:29:56,090
WHAT MADE THEM ACT LIKE THIS?

2385
01:29:56,157 --> 01:29:58,393
That'll be a hit or miss.

2386
01:30:07,335 --> 01:30:12,106
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
